00:00:12.597 --> 00:00:15.940
OK, so we will pick up on
the one topic that was not

00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:19.120
covered from two days ago
because you guys needed

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:22.520
to go play around with these
cellular automata first.

00:00:22.520 --> 00:00:24.120
So I will work
with the assumption

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:25.740
that everybody
here has now spent

00:00:25.740 --> 00:00:28.380
48 hours playing with those.

00:00:28.380 --> 00:00:31.352
But presumably because
of the sleep deprivation,

00:00:31.352 --> 00:00:32.810
you've forgotten
much of it by now.

00:00:32.810 --> 00:00:34.910
So we will cover some of it.

00:00:34.910 --> 00:00:40.800
OK, back to that issue
of fractals and butterfly

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:43.210
effects and that whole
business that, by the time

00:00:43.210 --> 00:00:45.340
you look at chaotic
systems that are

00:00:45.340 --> 00:00:48.460
determinist but
aperiodical, that, when

00:00:48.460 --> 00:00:51.030
they seem to be lines
crossing, getting back

00:00:51.030 --> 00:00:53.660
into the same spot,
look closely enough

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:56.624
and they're not going
to actually be touching.

00:00:56.624 --> 00:00:59.200
And the centerpiece
of why that matters

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:01.920
was that whole
business of, these

00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:03.190
both appear to be the same.

00:01:03.190 --> 00:01:04.610
And take them out
a decimal place

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:05.901
and they're actually different.

00:01:05.901 --> 00:01:08.030
And a gazillion
decimal places out.

00:01:08.030 --> 00:01:11.840
And the entire sort of rationale
for thinking in that way

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:15.960
is the notion that a very
small difference here

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:19.560
can make a difference
one step to the left.

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:25.380
And a million decimal places
out there, a small difference,

00:01:25.380 --> 00:01:28.560
will make a difference
one before that.

00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:33.040
In a scale-free way, a fractal,
this here, a difference here,

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:35.950
a million decimal places
out is just as likely

00:01:35.950 --> 00:01:39.710
to have consequences for
one over as this one for one

00:01:39.710 --> 00:01:42.310
over fractal, scale
free, all of that.

00:01:42.310 --> 00:01:45.150
But the critical thing
that is encompassed in this

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:48.400
is the notion that
tiny little differences

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:52.010
can have consequences
that magnify and magnify

00:01:52.010 --> 00:01:56.080
and amplify into a
butterfly effect.

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:59.020
So cellular automata
are a great way

00:01:59.020 --> 00:02:01.870
of seeing this principle along
with a number of others that

00:02:01.870 --> 00:02:03.330
are relevant to all of this.

00:02:03.330 --> 00:02:06.430
OK, so we start off
with the very first one.

00:02:06.430 --> 00:02:09.410
And this is the one
that you no doubt first

00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:12.530
discovered is a pattern,
which made you deeply happy.

00:02:12.530 --> 00:02:14.490
And if you follow
the rules, it was

00:02:14.490 --> 00:02:17.650
starting there-- was this--
which way is this facing,

00:02:17.650 --> 00:02:18.610
starting at the bottom.

00:02:24.090 --> 00:02:26.570
OK, this is starting
at the bottom.

00:02:26.570 --> 00:02:30.540
And what you see is
these very simple rules.

00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:34.290
And out of it emerges a
whole complex pattern.

00:02:34.290 --> 00:02:36.600
And we'll be seeing
shortly the features

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:39.470
of this that perfectly match
what the requirements are

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:41.540
for emergent complexity.

00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:46.230
But we'll see as the elements
are lots of constituents,

00:02:46.230 --> 00:02:47.850
lots of building blocks.

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:50.370
The building blocks
being very simple.

00:02:50.370 --> 00:02:51.230
They're binary.

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:54.330
Either they are
filled or not filled.

00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:59.420
Extremely simple rules as to
how the next generation gets

00:02:59.420 --> 00:03:01.250
formed.

00:03:01.250 --> 00:03:05.680
And in terms of the extremely
simple rules, none of the rules

00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:08.980
have anything to do with other
than the next generation.

00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:13.370
It is all local rules built
around what the neighborhood is

00:03:13.370 --> 00:03:14.810
like for each one of these.

00:03:14.810 --> 00:03:16.530
So you put it
together, and out come

00:03:16.530 --> 00:03:18.960
these very structured
patterns like these.

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:20.470
And this is great.

00:03:20.470 --> 00:03:22.070
This is very exciting.

00:03:22.070 --> 00:03:25.350
Except this isn't
what you usually get.

00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:28.180
In most of these cellular
automata systems, where

00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:32.160
you start off with an initial
condition and a simple set

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:35.470
of local neighbor rules for
how you get reproduction

00:03:35.470 --> 00:03:38.500
into the next
generations, in most cases

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:41.190
the patterns stop after a while.

00:03:41.190 --> 00:03:43.420
In the vast majority,
they stop, they

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:45.868
hit a wall, they go extinct.

00:03:45.868 --> 00:03:47.540
Aha.

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:48.980
Two terms that
I've already stuck

00:03:48.980 --> 00:03:51.510
in here that are
biological metaphors

00:03:51.510 --> 00:03:54.420
start to seem less
metaphorical after a while.

00:03:54.420 --> 00:03:57.250
First off, the notion that
going from here to here to here

00:03:57.250 --> 00:04:01.880
to here represents
each next generation.

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:03.900
And the notion that,
as we were just now,

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:07.990
that the vast majority of
these cellular automata systems

00:04:07.990 --> 00:04:09.150
go extinct.

00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:11.150
They fail after a while.

00:04:11.150 --> 00:04:13.210
So it's a very small subset.

00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:16.220
What you then also
see is-- in some ways

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:18.300
the critical point in
this whole business--

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:22.680
is the relatively small
number of starting states

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:27.410
that succeed produce a
remarkably small number

00:04:27.410 --> 00:04:32.940
of mature states that all look
very similar to each other.

00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:36.390
In other words, you can
start with a whole bunch

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:40.010
of different conditions,
and you will wind up

00:04:40.010 --> 00:04:44.040
with a bunch of smaller number
of stereotypical patterns.

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:46.150
Half of the cellular
automata that

00:04:46.150 --> 00:04:48.100
wind up taking
off look something

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:49.810
like this with this pattern.

00:04:49.810 --> 00:04:51.120
What are we seeing?

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:52.670
Convergence.

00:04:52.670 --> 00:04:53.770
Convergence.

00:04:53.770 --> 00:04:58.190
The notion that you can start
with different forms and they

00:04:58.190 --> 00:05:00.040
will converge over time.

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:00.710
What's this?

00:05:00.710 --> 00:05:03.080
Well, you just proved you
look at the mature form

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:06.330
and you can't know
the starting state.

00:05:06.330 --> 00:05:10.110
The other thing is, starting
at the beginning just looking

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:12.520
at this line,
there is no way you

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:16.260
can tell what it's going to look
like 20 generations from now.

00:05:16.260 --> 00:05:18.310
You've got to march through it.

00:05:18.310 --> 00:05:20.840
In other words,
the starting state

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:24.070
gives you no predictive
power about the mature state.

00:05:24.070 --> 00:05:26.490
This is a nonlinear system.

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:29.090
The cellular
automata encapsulates

00:05:29.090 --> 00:05:33.000
this, this business that
most of these go extinct.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.610
Only a relatively few number
of mature forms exist.

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:38.420
It shows convergence.

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:40.660
Very different starting
states can converge

00:05:40.660 --> 00:05:42.340
into the same sort of patterns.

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:46.060
And minor differences
in the starting state

00:05:46.060 --> 00:05:50.530
can extend into very
different consequences.

00:05:50.530 --> 00:05:53.400
It shows, in other
words, butterfly effects.

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:56.570
OK, so appreciating this a bit.

00:05:56.570 --> 00:05:58.650
So what we did was then
go to example number

00:05:58.650 --> 00:06:01.010
two, where we changed
the starting state

00:06:01.010 --> 00:06:02.030
just a little bit here.

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:03.790
We shifted around
some of the boxes.

00:06:03.790 --> 00:06:06.570
And what you see is something
that looks roughly the same,

00:06:06.570 --> 00:06:07.980
but it's not exactly the same.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:10.310
But it's the same
general feel to it.

00:06:10.310 --> 00:06:11.910
So that's great.

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:15.430
But then we started an
exercise of starting off

00:06:15.430 --> 00:06:18.870
with the initial boxes.

00:06:18.870 --> 00:06:19.880
This goes that way.

00:06:19.880 --> 00:06:24.210
The initial boxes evenly spaced
with one space between them

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:26.120
and applied the
rules from there.

00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:27.540
And this is what you get.

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:32.100
Totally boring, static,
inorganic, inanimate.

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:34.290
This is what it does
for the rest of time.

00:06:34.290 --> 00:06:37.110
What this exercise then
did, going to number four,

00:06:37.110 --> 00:06:40.170
is what if we now
spaced two boxes

00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:41.810
between each one of these?

00:06:41.810 --> 00:06:44.970
And here we have an extinction.

00:06:44.970 --> 00:06:46.970
This is one of those
where it hits a wall,

00:06:46.970 --> 00:06:49.980
and all the next
lines are empty.

00:06:49.980 --> 00:06:53.730
OK, how about three boxes in
between the starting states?

00:06:53.730 --> 00:06:56.530
OK, another form of extinction.

00:06:56.530 --> 00:06:59.990
OK, how about four boxes
between the starting states?

00:06:59.990 --> 00:07:03.810
And suddenly, something
very dynamic takes off.

00:07:03.810 --> 00:07:06.540
Applying the same rules,
and all you've done

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:09.420
is change the spacing
between the starting states.

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:13.830
And look at, for one thing, how
close this was to going extinct

00:07:13.830 --> 00:07:17.140
up there on top, how
asymmetrical the pattern is

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:18.100
that comes out.

00:07:18.100 --> 00:07:21.792
And this particular one will
stay asymmetrical forever.

00:07:21.792 --> 00:07:24.140
And the ways in
which that generated

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:26.070
something very unexpected.

00:07:26.070 --> 00:07:29.040
There is no way you
could sit there a priori

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:33.400
and say, hm, one box in between
generates something that

00:07:33.400 --> 00:07:34.350
looks inanimate.

00:07:34.350 --> 00:07:35.910
Two boxes, not going to work.

00:07:35.910 --> 00:07:36.790
Three boxes, yeah.

00:07:36.790 --> 00:07:38.960
Somewhere around four
boxes in between.

00:07:38.960 --> 00:07:41.900
That's when dynamic
systems suddenly take off.

00:07:41.900 --> 00:07:44.180
There is no way
to have known that

00:07:44.180 --> 00:07:47.600
before without marching through
this and actually seeing.

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:51.920
Starting state tells you
nothing about the mature state.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:54.610
Then we space it even further.

00:07:54.610 --> 00:07:58.080
And what we get is
something similar again.

00:07:58.080 --> 00:07:59.270
This one is symmetrical.

00:07:59.270 --> 00:08:01.340
It is somewhat different
from the previous one,

00:08:01.340 --> 00:08:03.430
but it's the same
sorts of patterns

00:08:03.430 --> 00:08:05.390
that come up over and over.

00:08:05.390 --> 00:08:08.400
So what we've seen here
is, by starting state,

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:11.310
minor differences,
big divergence

00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:15.600
between going extinct versus
being a viable pattern.

00:08:15.600 --> 00:08:18.390
Minor differences in starting
state, big divergence

00:08:18.390 --> 00:08:21.110
between symmetrical and
asymmetrical patterns.

00:08:21.110 --> 00:08:24.800
Tiny differences,
butterfly effects.

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:26.680
OK, next.

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:35.539
Looking at the consequences here
of introducing some asymmetry

00:08:35.539 --> 00:08:36.539
from the very beginning.

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:42.020
The one on the left up on top
has four boxes and four boxes.

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:43.289
It has eight boxes.

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:46.620
The one on top has eight boxes
on the left, and the one on top

00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:49.660
on the right, just adding in
one extra box on the side,

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:50.910
so it's four and five.

00:08:50.910 --> 00:08:53.690
Adding a little asymmetry,
and what you see

00:08:53.690 --> 00:08:55.950
is a very different pattern.

00:08:55.950 --> 00:08:57.690
And one of the things
you tend to see

00:08:57.690 --> 00:09:03.020
in these pseudo-animate living
pattern systems is starting

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:06.850
states of asymmetry produce
more dynamic systems,

00:09:06.850 --> 00:09:10.930
more dynamic patterns than
even symmetrical ones.

00:09:10.930 --> 00:09:14.320
That's one of the only rules
that comes out of there.

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:17.940
So we're seeing now minor
little differences producing

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:20.400
major different consequences.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:23.780
Divergencies, butterfly effects.

00:09:23.780 --> 00:09:27.945
Now showing this
in a different way.

00:09:27.945 --> 00:09:34.520
And what we've got here are
four different starting state

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:35.720
conditions.

00:09:35.720 --> 00:09:37.220
The one on the far
left is, in fact,

00:09:37.220 --> 00:09:39.380
the one from the previous
one, the four and four.

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:41.430
Four different starting
state conditions

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:44.504
where they're not enormously
related to each other.

00:09:44.504 --> 00:09:46.920
The first one against the other
three, but the other three

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:48.230
have minor differences.

00:09:48.230 --> 00:09:50.210
And the whole thing
is, two of these

00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:54.040
are identical after the
first 20 generations or so.

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:57.170
This one and this one.

00:09:57.170 --> 00:09:59.830
The two of them are
identical, and for the rest

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:01.880
of the universe
they will produce

00:10:01.880 --> 00:10:03.600
the same identical pattern.

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:07.780
And looking at the mature
state, you show up on the scene

00:10:07.780 --> 00:10:11.570
somewhere halfway down, and
you could never ever know

00:10:11.570 --> 00:10:13.210
what the starting state was.

00:10:13.210 --> 00:10:16.550
Did it start like this or
did it start like this?

00:10:16.550 --> 00:10:18.680
A convergency here.

00:10:18.680 --> 00:10:21.044
And in this case, it's
another one of those rules.

00:10:21.044 --> 00:10:22.710
Knowing the starting
state doesn't allow

00:10:22.710 --> 00:10:24.230
you to predict the mature form.

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:27.090
Knowing the mature
form, you don't

00:10:27.090 --> 00:10:30.080
know which particular starting
state brought it about.

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:31.790
And the only way
to figure it out

00:10:31.790 --> 00:10:35.030
is to stepwise go
through the whole process

00:10:35.030 --> 00:10:39.040
because you can't just
iterate by a blueprint.

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:39.960
There is no blueprint.

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:44.250
Finally, the last
one was giving you,

00:10:44.250 --> 00:10:46.330
instead of different
starting boxes

00:10:46.330 --> 00:10:49.420
in each case with the
same reproduction rule,

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:51.610
the last one was the
same starting pattern

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:54.340
of boxes with
different, slightly

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:56.160
different, reproductive rules.

00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:59.950
And what you see here are
totally different outcomes,

00:10:59.950 --> 00:11:01.430
depending on which variant.

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:04.000
We have the beloved
one on the top left.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
And you see here, by slightly
changing the nearest neighbor

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.560
rules, if and only
if there is one

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:12.390
neighbor with this
property, if and only

00:11:12.390 --> 00:11:13.980
if there's two neighbors.

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:15.600
And working through
that way, and you

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:20.350
see remarkably divergent
outcomes for one thing.

00:11:20.350 --> 00:11:22.060
You see that the
majority of them

00:11:22.060 --> 00:11:25.770
produce something very
boring, either boring extinct

00:11:25.770 --> 00:11:29.750
or boring repetitive in
a very undynamic way.

00:11:29.750 --> 00:11:35.150
Only a small subset
produce lively, animated,

00:11:35.150 --> 00:11:36.652
living systems.

00:11:36.652 --> 00:11:38.860
So we're seeing a whole
bunch of biological metaphors

00:11:38.860 --> 00:11:41.857
here over and over and over,
which is the starting states.

00:11:41.857 --> 00:11:43.440
You don't know the
mature, the mature,

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:44.856
you don't know the
starting state.

00:11:44.856 --> 00:11:48.630
The generations, very simple
rules for generations,

00:11:48.630 --> 00:11:50.240
going one to the next.

00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:52.610
What we see also is
the vast majority

00:11:52.610 --> 00:11:56.540
go extinct and produce,
either go extinct

00:11:56.540 --> 00:12:00.950
or some repetitive, very boring,
crystallized type structure.

00:12:00.950 --> 00:12:03.580
A small subset, a
tiny subset, produce,

00:12:03.580 --> 00:12:05.460
instead, dynamic patterns.

00:12:05.460 --> 00:12:09.000
And knowing what the
starting state is is not

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.140
going to give you any
predictability whatsoever of,

00:12:12.140 --> 00:12:14.740
is this going to produce
a dynamic pattern or not?

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:17.620
Nor does it allow you to look at
a bunch of the starting states

00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:20.420
and say, those two
are going to produce

00:12:20.420 --> 00:12:22.680
the same mature pattern.

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:25.820
And these are all
properties of the evolution

00:12:25.820 --> 00:12:28.000
of different living systems.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.110
So you begin to see,
OK, cellular automata.

00:12:31.110 --> 00:12:32.620
Do you see some of
these principles?

00:12:32.620 --> 00:12:36.470
The simplest level out
there in the natural world

00:12:36.470 --> 00:12:41.481
is looking at all sorts of
shells, seashells and tortoise

00:12:41.481 --> 00:12:43.870
shells by the seashore
and whatevers.

00:12:43.870 --> 00:12:47.980
And they all have
patterning on them

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:53.410
that is derived from that
first cellular automata

00:12:53.410 --> 00:12:57.610
rule, producing patterns that
look a whole lot like these.

00:12:57.610 --> 00:13:01.750
And go online and look for them
because I didn't get around

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:05.400
to it in time, but producing
all sorts of patterns in nature.

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:07.070
Very common ones.

00:13:07.070 --> 00:13:08.420
What does that tell you?

00:13:08.420 --> 00:13:13.420
Very simple rules for generating
the same complex patterns

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:16.560
and different starting
states, cellular automata

00:13:16.560 --> 00:13:19.110
and properties here.

00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:21.850
Another thing in a
living biological system

00:13:21.850 --> 00:13:23.910
that begins to suggest this.

00:13:23.910 --> 00:13:28.859
OK, so I do this
research in East Africa.

00:13:28.859 --> 00:13:30.400
And every now and
then over the years

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:32.860
I've gone to this mountain
called Mount Kenya, which

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:34.250
is on the equator.

00:13:34.250 --> 00:13:36.140
It's about 17,000 feet.

00:13:36.140 --> 00:13:37.770
It's got glaciers up on top.

00:13:37.770 --> 00:13:40.530
So this is an equatorial
glacial mountain.

00:13:40.530 --> 00:13:43.570
And you go up to about
the 15,000-foot zone,

00:13:43.570 --> 00:13:46.910
and there's like--
it's more land.

00:13:46.910 --> 00:13:49.030
Almost everything is dead
up there from the cold.

00:13:49.030 --> 00:13:50.500
And there's
basically only, like,

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:53.580
four or five different
types of plants up there.

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:57.610
Oh, already a very small
number that survive

00:13:57.610 --> 00:13:58.780
in that environment.

00:13:58.780 --> 00:14:01.820
And each one of them is
very bizarre and distinctive

00:14:01.820 --> 00:14:02.400
looking.

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:03.858
There's one of them
that looks like

00:14:03.858 --> 00:14:06.680
a little, like, rosebud
thing, except it's

00:14:06.680 --> 00:14:08.580
about 5 feet across.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:10.220
And then there's
another one that

00:14:10.220 --> 00:14:12.350
has sort of a sprouty
thing like this and then

00:14:12.350 --> 00:14:15.670
a big central cactus-looking
thing that isn't really cactus.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:18.240
So there's a few of
these really distinctive,

00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:20.060
bizarre-looking plants.

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:22.350
And in some way or
other, that's what

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:24.650
it takes to survive up there.

00:14:24.650 --> 00:14:28.640
So I have this friend who
does research up in the Andes.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:30.540
And he does botany
stuff up there.

00:14:30.540 --> 00:14:35.100
And he goes into this one range
there that is on the equator

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:37.410
and high enough that
there's glaciers up there.

00:14:37.410 --> 00:14:40.600
Ah, a glacial equatorial
mountain on the other side

00:14:40.600 --> 00:14:41.370
of the globe.

00:14:41.370 --> 00:14:43.110
So one day I'm sitting
around and looking

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:44.650
at some of his pictures there.

00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:48.900
And suddenly I look and say,
that's the exact same plant.

00:14:48.900 --> 00:14:52.310
That's the big rosebud plant
that is in Mount Kenya.

00:14:52.310 --> 00:14:54.990
And oh, my god, that's
the tall sprouty one.

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:56.770
And say, it's the
exact same plant.

00:14:56.770 --> 00:14:58.650
How can that plant
be over there?

00:14:58.650 --> 00:15:02.720
And we go rummage around in
his botany taxonomy stuff,

00:15:02.720 --> 00:15:06.090
and they are completely
unrelated plants.

00:15:06.090 --> 00:15:10.120
They are taxonomically of
no connection whatsoever.

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:15.380
But what they've done is
converged onto the same shape.

00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:18.030
And in some mysterious
way, if you're

00:15:18.030 --> 00:15:21.600
going to be a plant growing
on the equator at about

00:15:21.600 --> 00:15:25.330
15,000 feet, there's only about
four or five different ways

00:15:25.330 --> 00:15:26.460
of appearing.

00:15:26.460 --> 00:15:28.650
There is massive convergence.

00:15:28.650 --> 00:15:30.690
And there's only
four or five ways

00:15:30.690 --> 00:15:33.580
that you can survive an
environment like that.

00:15:33.580 --> 00:15:37.600
You get organisms in
very dry environments,

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:40.570
and there's, like,
only four or five ways

00:15:40.570 --> 00:15:43.080
that you can go about being
an organism that's super

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:45.070
efficient at retaining water.

00:15:45.070 --> 00:15:48.770
And those are the only
ones you see amongst them.

00:15:48.770 --> 00:15:51.970
Desert animals, and
completely unrelated ones,

00:15:51.970 --> 00:15:54.770
have converged onto some
of the same solutions.

00:15:54.770 --> 00:15:56.800
There's only a
very finite number

00:15:56.800 --> 00:16:00.010
of ways to do legs
and locomotion.

00:16:00.010 --> 00:16:04.140
Two is good, four, weirdo
things that fly of six,

00:16:04.140 --> 00:16:05.270
creepy things have eight.

00:16:05.270 --> 00:16:06.860
You don't find seven.

00:16:06.860 --> 00:16:08.200
You don't find three.

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:11.530
You find some of the solutions
here are immensely different

00:16:11.530 --> 00:16:13.690
starting states
and have converged.

00:16:13.690 --> 00:16:17.400
What we see is in these living
systems over and over stuff

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:19.740
that look like
cellular automata,

00:16:19.740 --> 00:16:25.240
where slight differences magnify
enormously butterfly effects,

00:16:25.240 --> 00:16:28.930
where you are modeling living
systems in a very real way.

00:16:28.930 --> 00:16:30.540
Most of them go extinct.

00:16:30.540 --> 00:16:32.130
Divergence, convergence.

00:16:32.130 --> 00:16:35.460
And where each one of these
you get the smaller number,

00:16:35.460 --> 00:16:38.890
reflecting the fact that there's
only a limited number of ways

00:16:38.890 --> 00:16:42.850
of doing rain forest,
temperate zone rain forest

00:16:42.850 --> 00:16:44.240
in the Pacific Northwest.

00:16:44.240 --> 00:16:46.290
There's only a
limited number of ways

00:16:46.290 --> 00:16:48.920
of doing tundra in Miami Beach.

00:16:48.920 --> 00:16:50.660
There's only a limited
number of ways.

00:16:50.660 --> 00:16:53.080
In all of these,
this convergence,

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:56.800
and always reflecting that
these are cellular automata.

00:16:56.800 --> 00:16:57.440
OK.

00:16:57.440 --> 00:17:02.970
So hopefully you are now
feeling desperately regretful

00:17:02.970 --> 00:17:05.480
that you didn't spend the
last few days doing this

00:17:05.480 --> 00:17:07.890
because these are
so heartwarming.

00:17:07.890 --> 00:17:10.650
If you want to read a book
that nobody in their right mind

00:17:10.650 --> 00:17:14.550
should read, it's a book by this
guy named Steve Wolfram, who's

00:17:14.550 --> 00:17:19.200
one of the gods of
computers and math

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:21.750
and was one of the sort of
people who first developed

00:17:21.750 --> 00:17:23.829
cellular automata.

00:17:23.829 --> 00:17:26.800
And by all reports
probably one of the largest

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:28.550
egos on the planet.

00:17:28.550 --> 00:17:30.730
And he published a
book, self-published it,

00:17:30.730 --> 00:17:32.580
a few years ago, which
he can because he

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:36.030
is grotesquely wealthy, from
some of his computer programs.

00:17:36.030 --> 00:17:39.500
And just showing what a
low-key sort of humble guy

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:43.110
he is, he called the book
A New Kind of Science,

00:17:43.110 --> 00:17:46.040
just showing that
he wasn't just going

00:17:46.040 --> 00:17:48.830
from some little piddly new
way of viewing the world,

00:17:48.830 --> 00:17:51.580
but here was his
new type of science.

00:17:51.580 --> 00:17:53.990
And the book is
about 1,200 pages.

00:17:53.990 --> 00:17:55.750
And I suspect not
even his mother

00:17:55.750 --> 00:17:58.580
has read the thing it
is so impenetrable.

00:17:58.580 --> 00:18:00.790
And it sold a gazillion copies.

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:03.450
And almost all of them are
sitting in people's garages

00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:06.500
now, weighting down drain pipes
because no one can actually

00:18:06.500 --> 00:18:07.390
read this thing.

00:18:07.390 --> 00:18:09.830
But an awful lot of
what the book is about

00:18:09.830 --> 00:18:15.710
are patterns in nature coded
for by very simple local rules.

00:18:15.710 --> 00:18:17.560
And the simple fact
of that, you've

00:18:17.560 --> 00:18:21.480
got a lot of very smart people
doing this cellular automata

00:18:21.480 --> 00:18:22.360
stuff.

00:18:22.360 --> 00:18:24.880
And they can't
come up with rules

00:18:24.880 --> 00:18:28.570
where you could look at
something beforehand a priori

00:18:28.570 --> 00:18:31.150
and know this one
is going to survive,

00:18:31.150 --> 00:18:33.390
this one is going to
go extinct, those two

00:18:33.390 --> 00:18:35.270
are going to turn
the same, these two

00:18:35.270 --> 00:18:37.360
that differ by a
slight smidgen are

00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:39.360
going to turn out to be
enormously different.

00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:41.170
There's no rules for it.

00:18:41.170 --> 00:18:43.250
And the book has all
sorts of cool pictures

00:18:43.250 --> 00:18:45.885
of a cellular automata
looking things out in nature.

00:18:45.885 --> 00:18:50.386
And go buy it for
somebody's birthday

00:18:50.386 --> 00:18:52.885
and see if they're not grateful
for the rest of their lives.

00:18:52.885 --> 00:18:55.580
But his whole argument
there is, these

00:18:55.580 --> 00:19:00.080
show ways in which you can code
for a lot of the complexity

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:05.050
in the natural world with
small numbers of simple rules.

00:19:05.050 --> 00:19:08.020
This whole business
of emergence.

00:19:08.020 --> 00:19:09.920
This sets us up
now for beginning

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:11.720
to look at some of
the ways in which we

00:19:11.720 --> 00:19:15.180
hit a wall the other day, ways
in which the reductive model

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:18.190
of understanding the universe
stops working after a while.

00:19:18.190 --> 00:19:20.700
One version being the
problem of not having

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:22.660
enough numbers of things.

00:19:22.660 --> 00:19:25.450
Not having enough
neurons to do grandmother

00:19:25.450 --> 00:19:28.460
neurons beyond Jennifer
Aniston, that whole business

00:19:28.460 --> 00:19:30.260
that you simply
don't have enough

00:19:30.260 --> 00:19:33.660
neurons to do that beyond just
the rare ones now and then.

00:19:33.660 --> 00:19:35.280
And what do you get instead?

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:37.580
What has the solution
turned out to be?

00:19:37.580 --> 00:19:40.905
This field that people focus
on now called neural networks.

00:19:43.565 --> 00:19:48.400
And the point of neural networks
is that information, again,

00:19:48.400 --> 00:19:51.460
is not coded in a single
molecule, single synapse,

00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:53.272
single neuron, one neuron.

00:19:53.272 --> 00:19:55.230
This neuron knows one
thing and one thing only,

00:19:55.230 --> 00:19:57.480
which is when there's
a dot there, instead,

00:19:57.480 --> 00:20:00.150
information is
coded in networks,

00:20:00.150 --> 00:20:03.520
in patterns of
neural activation.

00:20:03.520 --> 00:20:05.730
And just to give you
an example, and this is

00:20:05.730 --> 00:20:06.980
one that's in the Zebra book.

00:20:06.980 --> 00:20:09.130
And anyone who is in
Biocore I do this one,

00:20:09.130 --> 00:20:11.710
and I do it because
I at one point

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:13.960
learned the name of three
impressionist painters,

00:20:13.960 --> 00:20:15.240
except they're not
coming to mind right now.

00:20:15.240 --> 00:20:16.760
OK, so you've got two layers.

00:20:16.760 --> 00:20:18.800
Here's what a neural
network would look like.

00:20:18.800 --> 00:20:20.410
A two-layer one.

00:20:20.410 --> 00:20:25.000
These neurons on the bottom
are boring, simple, Hubel and

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.260
Wiesel-type neurons
from the other day,

00:20:27.260 --> 00:20:30.540
where each neuron knows one
thing and one thing only.

00:20:30.540 --> 00:20:34.660
This one knows how to
recognize Gauguin paintings,

00:20:34.660 --> 00:20:38.797
this one recognizes Van
Gogh, and this one Monet.

00:20:38.797 --> 00:20:40.050
OK.

00:20:40.050 --> 00:20:43.090
Each one of them is-- obviously
there is no Hubel and Wiesel

00:20:43.090 --> 00:20:44.870
neuron on Earth
that's like that.

00:20:44.870 --> 00:20:46.410
But just for our purposes.

00:20:46.410 --> 00:20:48.390
They now project up
to this next layer.

00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:52.520
Note this neuron projects
to one, two, and three.

00:20:52.520 --> 00:20:54.660
This to two, three, and four.

00:20:54.660 --> 00:20:56.180
This to three, four, and five.

00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:58.800
So what does this
neuron know about?

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:01.160
This one knows how
to recognize Gauguin.

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:04.200
It's only getting
information from this neuron.

00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:06.780
It's another one of those
Hubel and Wiesel type,

00:21:06.780 --> 00:21:08.910
I know one fact
and one fact only.

00:21:08.910 --> 00:21:11.840
This one here is
another one of those.

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:14.830
What does this neuron
know about in the middle?

00:21:14.830 --> 00:21:17.400
That's the neuron that
knows how to recognize

00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:19.220
Impressionist paintings.

00:21:19.220 --> 00:21:21.780
That's the one that
says, I can't tell you

00:21:21.780 --> 00:21:25.150
who the artist is, but it's
one of those Impressionists.

00:21:25.150 --> 00:21:27.230
It's not one of
those Dutch masters.

00:21:27.230 --> 00:21:29.490
It's an Impressionist painting.

00:21:29.490 --> 00:21:33.460
And this one does it because
it is getting information that

00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:35.780
is not available to these guys.

00:21:35.780 --> 00:21:39.270
It is getting information
at the intersection

00:21:39.270 --> 00:21:42.100
of all these specific examples.

00:21:42.100 --> 00:21:45.150
These ones, number
two and four, those

00:21:45.150 --> 00:21:47.920
are ones that recognize
Impressionist paintings also,

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:50.800
but they're not as accurate
at it as number three

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:53.960
because they've got less
examples to work off of.

00:21:53.960 --> 00:21:56.040
This is how a
network would work.

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:58.890
And what that suddenly
begins to explain

00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:02.800
is something about the human
brain versus a computer.

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:06.840
Computers are amazing at doing
sequential analytical stuff.

00:22:06.840 --> 00:22:10.730
Like, you get calculator
things inside Cheerio boxes

00:22:10.730 --> 00:22:12.860
that can do more things
than the human brain can

00:22:12.860 --> 00:22:14.600
do computationally.

00:22:14.600 --> 00:22:17.890
But what we can do is
parallel processing.

00:22:17.890 --> 00:22:22.940
What we can do is patterns,
resemblances, similarities,

00:22:22.940 --> 00:22:26.300
metaphorical similarities,
physical similarities.

00:22:26.300 --> 00:22:29.450
And that's why you need
networks like these.

00:22:29.450 --> 00:22:33.130
You don't need neurons that
know one fact and one fact only.

00:22:33.130 --> 00:22:35.570
You need neurons
where each one of them

00:22:35.570 --> 00:22:38.760
is at the intersection of a
whole bunch of other inputs.

00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:40.270
OK, example.

00:22:40.270 --> 00:22:42.260
So now suppose
you've got a network.

00:22:42.260 --> 00:22:44.590
There's one neuron
which fires, and there's

00:22:44.590 --> 00:22:47.960
a whole bunch of neurons sort
of sending projections into it.

00:22:47.960 --> 00:22:51.090
And this is a neuron
for remembering

00:22:51.090 --> 00:22:52.680
the name of that guy.

00:22:52.680 --> 00:22:54.020
What was the name of that guy?

00:22:54.020 --> 00:22:56.350
That guy, he was that
Impressionist painter.

00:22:56.350 --> 00:22:58.630
So suddenly your
Impressionist painter network

00:22:58.630 --> 00:23:01.110
is activating and
firing at this neuron.

00:23:01.110 --> 00:23:04.120
So it's sitting there.

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:08.060
So this is-- now you've got
your whole Impressionist network

00:23:08.060 --> 00:23:08.820
that's activated.

00:23:08.820 --> 00:23:10.700
What was the name of that guy?

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:12.850
He was an Impressionist painter.

00:23:12.850 --> 00:23:16.770
He painted women dancers
a lot of the time.

00:23:16.770 --> 00:23:19.260
So people who painted dancers.

00:23:19.260 --> 00:23:20.640
But it wasn't Degas.

00:23:20.640 --> 00:23:23.870
OK, so your "it's not Degas"
circuit going in there.

00:23:23.870 --> 00:23:25.110
And what was that guy's name?

00:23:25.110 --> 00:23:27.240
God, I had that seventh
grade art teacher

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:28.440
who loved this guy's work.

00:23:28.440 --> 00:23:31.090
If I could remember her name,
I would remember his name.

00:23:31.090 --> 00:23:33.502
Oh, remember the time
I was at the museum

00:23:33.502 --> 00:23:35.960
and there was that really cute
person who seemed to like it

00:23:35.960 --> 00:23:37.942
and I had to pretend
I liked this guy also

00:23:37.942 --> 00:23:39.400
and it didn't work
out nonetheless?

00:23:39.400 --> 00:23:40.160
And going through.

00:23:40.160 --> 00:23:41.470
And oh, what's the name?

00:23:41.470 --> 00:23:44.440
There's that stupid pun about
the guy, he's really short.

00:23:44.440 --> 00:23:46.980
And something about the
tracks being too loose.

00:23:46.980 --> 00:23:48.590
Ah, Toulous-Lautrec.

00:23:48.590 --> 00:23:51.520
And suddenly it pops
out there, and you've

00:23:51.520 --> 00:23:54.120
got enough of these
inputs coming in there.

00:23:54.120 --> 00:23:57.360
And this is tip of
the tongue wiring.

00:23:57.360 --> 00:24:00.450
This is how you may not
be able to just remember

00:24:00.450 --> 00:24:01.750
the guy's name.

00:24:01.750 --> 00:24:04.500
Wait, he was the short guy
with a beard who hung out

00:24:04.500 --> 00:24:06.730
in bars and Parisian bars.

00:24:06.730 --> 00:24:09.590
And here was that
time in seventh grade.

00:24:09.590 --> 00:24:12.640
And enough of these inputs,
and suddenly out pops

00:24:12.640 --> 00:24:14.040
the information.

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:16.170
And what this begins
to tell you is,

00:24:16.170 --> 00:24:19.150
this is ways of
getting similarities.

00:24:19.150 --> 00:24:22.370
These are ways of getting
things that vaguely remind you.

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:25.440
This is a world where
humans can now do stuff

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:27.920
like have a piece of
music that reminds

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:30.280
them of a certain
artist because they

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:32.810
both have similar coloration.

00:24:32.810 --> 00:24:35.430
And that's something
that makes sense to us.

00:24:35.430 --> 00:24:37.640
That's something that can
work because, what you then

00:24:37.640 --> 00:24:41.370
begin to see is, every one
of these neurons, this one,

00:24:41.370 --> 00:24:43.900
for example,
Impressionist neurons.

00:24:43.900 --> 00:24:47.690
This one may also be at the
intersection of another network

00:24:47.690 --> 00:24:51.980
that's going this way,
a network of French guys

00:24:51.980 --> 00:24:53.460
from the last century.

00:24:53.460 --> 00:24:57.260
And it may be part of
another network of people

00:24:57.260 --> 00:24:58.909
whose names are
hard to pronounce

00:24:58.909 --> 00:25:00.950
so you're anxious about
saying them in a lecture.

00:25:00.950 --> 00:25:03.221
Or the intersection--
and each one of these

00:25:03.221 --> 00:25:05.596
is going to be an intersection
of a whole bunch of these.

00:25:05.596 --> 00:25:08.310
All of these networks,
what does that do?

00:25:08.310 --> 00:25:11.020
That's what you can do
that a computer can't.

00:25:11.020 --> 00:25:14.900
You see similarities,
similes, metaphors.

00:25:14.900 --> 00:25:17.950
And somewhere in there you get
something really important,

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:23.790
which is the ones, the networks,
that have wider expanses that

00:25:23.790 --> 00:25:26.300
connect to a broader
number of neurons

00:25:26.300 --> 00:25:30.570
in a very simple,
artificial, idiotic way.

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:33.710
That's kind of what
creativity would have to be,

00:25:33.710 --> 00:25:36.790
networks that are
spreading far wider

00:25:36.790 --> 00:25:39.530
than in some other individual.

00:25:39.530 --> 00:25:42.410
It is literally
making connections

00:25:42.410 --> 00:25:44.950
that neurons in another
individual does not.

00:25:44.950 --> 00:25:48.810
And suddenly you have
a world where everyone

00:25:48.810 --> 00:25:51.220
knows this one is a face.

00:25:51.220 --> 00:25:54.930
And it was only a limited
number of people who ever

00:25:54.930 --> 00:25:56.820
decided that this one's a face.

00:25:56.820 --> 00:26:00.910
And in some level Picasso had
a different network, a broader

00:26:00.910 --> 00:26:04.240
one, as to what could
constitute a face.

00:26:04.240 --> 00:26:07.030
A broader network
in some way is going

00:26:07.030 --> 00:26:11.030
to have to be wiring
that is more divergent.

00:26:11.030 --> 00:26:14.260
And at the intersection
of a bunch of networks

00:26:14.260 --> 00:26:16.412
that are acting in
a convergent way.

00:26:16.412 --> 00:26:18.370
So what's some of the
evidence that it actually

00:26:18.370 --> 00:26:19.850
does work this way?

00:26:19.850 --> 00:26:25.240
You go and you stick electrodes
into neurons in the cortex,

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:28.960
and what you see, if the
world was entirely made up of,

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:32.650
like Hubel and Wiesel, one
piece of knowledge only, what

00:26:32.650 --> 00:26:35.700
you would see is you would find
neurons that each one responds

00:26:35.700 --> 00:26:37.400
to one single thing.

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:38.900
All these grandmother neurons.

00:26:38.900 --> 00:26:40.830
And instead, what
you see by the time

00:26:40.830 --> 00:26:44.080
you get to the interesting
part of the cortex

00:26:44.080 --> 00:26:47.339
past the first three
layers of the visual cortex

00:26:47.339 --> 00:26:49.130
and the first three
layers of the auditory.

00:26:49.130 --> 00:26:52.180
Once you get into
the 90% that's called

00:26:52.180 --> 00:26:53.895
the associational
cortex-- and it's

00:26:53.895 --> 00:26:55.270
called that because
nobody really

00:26:55.270 --> 00:26:57.910
knows what it does--
then what you see

00:26:57.910 --> 00:27:01.590
are neurons that are
multimodal in their responses.

00:27:01.590 --> 00:27:04.480
All sorts of things
stimulate them.

00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:06.720
And here we have a neuron
that's being stimulated

00:27:06.720 --> 00:27:10.470
by a type of painting, by
the knowledge of French guys,

00:27:10.470 --> 00:27:13.160
by something phonetic,
by all sorts--

00:27:13.160 --> 00:27:15.330
and they're multiresponsive.

00:27:15.330 --> 00:27:17.350
So that's what you
wind up seeing.

00:27:17.350 --> 00:27:19.530
The majority of
cortical neurons,

00:27:19.530 --> 00:27:21.530
when you record from
them with an electrode,

00:27:21.530 --> 00:27:23.020
they're not grandmother neurons.

00:27:23.020 --> 00:27:25.490
They're at the intersection
of a bunch of nets.

00:27:25.490 --> 00:27:27.140
More evidence for this.

00:27:27.140 --> 00:27:30.390
This was-- one of the grand
poobahs of neuroscience

00:27:30.390 --> 00:27:33.320
around the 1940s or so,
a guy named Karl Lashley.

00:27:33.320 --> 00:27:35.810
And obviously a
very different time

00:27:35.810 --> 00:27:37.900
in terms of thinking about
specification of brain

00:27:37.900 --> 00:27:38.670
function.

00:27:38.670 --> 00:27:42.470
And what he did was a
very systematic attempt

00:27:42.470 --> 00:27:44.930
to be able to show
where in the brain

00:27:44.930 --> 00:27:47.110
individual facts were stored.

00:27:47.110 --> 00:27:50.570
And the term for it at the time,
this jargony term, was engrams.

00:27:50.570 --> 00:27:54.390
He was searching for the
engram for different facts.

00:27:54.390 --> 00:27:56.180
And what he would
show was, he would

00:27:56.180 --> 00:27:59.930
destroy parts of the cortex
in an experimental animal.

00:27:59.930 --> 00:28:02.980
And he couldn't make the
information disappear.

00:28:02.980 --> 00:28:05.220
He would have to
destroy broader areas.

00:28:05.220 --> 00:28:07.150
And some of the knowledge,
some of the memory

00:28:07.150 --> 00:28:08.410
was still in there.

00:28:08.410 --> 00:28:10.630
And he concluded in
this famous paper

00:28:10.630 --> 00:28:12.736
in the search for the
engram that, according

00:28:12.736 --> 00:28:14.110
to all the science
he knew, there

00:28:14.110 --> 00:28:16.370
could be no such
thing as memory.

00:28:16.370 --> 00:28:18.760
And the reason why
was he was working

00:28:18.760 --> 00:28:21.220
with a model of being
able to-- there's

00:28:21.220 --> 00:28:23.860
a single neuron where,
if I could ablate it,

00:28:23.860 --> 00:28:26.200
I should be able to
now show in that rat

00:28:26.200 --> 00:28:29.540
that it's just lost the name
of its kindergarten teacher.

00:28:29.540 --> 00:28:33.190
And instead, you see
networks going on.

00:28:33.190 --> 00:28:35.630
You see the same thing
clinically in something

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:38.190
like people with
Alzheimer's disease.

00:28:38.190 --> 00:28:43.450
Early on in Alzheimer's, you
will lose, in these networks,

00:28:43.450 --> 00:28:46.750
you'll lose a neuron here or
you'll lose a neuron there

00:28:46.750 --> 00:28:48.650
when you're just
beginning to lose neurons.

00:28:48.650 --> 00:28:50.500
And what you see is,
clinically, in people

00:28:50.500 --> 00:28:55.130
with Alzheimer's, early on, it's
not that they forget things.

00:28:55.130 --> 00:28:57.410
It's not that memory is gone.

00:28:57.410 --> 00:28:59.540
It's just harder to get to.

00:28:59.540 --> 00:29:01.820
And you do this with
all sorts of testing,

00:29:01.820 --> 00:29:03.610
neuropsychological
testing, where

00:29:03.610 --> 00:29:07.690
you try to give the person
cues to pull it out.

00:29:07.690 --> 00:29:08.352
Example.

00:29:08.352 --> 00:29:10.560
You're giving somebody,
potentially with Alzheimer's,

00:29:10.560 --> 00:29:12.810
a classic orientation test.

00:29:12.810 --> 00:29:17.320
You ask them, OK, do you know
the name of the president?

00:29:17.320 --> 00:29:18.750
OK, they manage to get that.

00:29:18.750 --> 00:29:20.770
Do you know the name
of the last president?

00:29:20.770 --> 00:29:22.019
No idea.

00:29:22.019 --> 00:29:23.810
So now you give them
a little bit of cuing.

00:29:23.810 --> 00:29:25.184
OK, let me help
you a little bit.

00:29:25.184 --> 00:29:27.320
It's a one-syllable word.

00:29:27.320 --> 00:29:29.150
Still not there, even
though you've now

00:29:29.150 --> 00:29:33.260
activated the one-syllable word
network, obviously artificial.

00:29:33.260 --> 00:29:33.960
Still can't say.

00:29:33.960 --> 00:29:35.790
OK, let's make it a
little bit easier.

00:29:35.790 --> 00:29:39.970
It's things you could find
in a park, in a city park.

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:41.240
So you're activating that.

00:29:41.240 --> 00:29:42.890
No, still not coming out.

00:29:42.890 --> 00:29:45.750
And then you give even more
explicit priming there.

00:29:45.750 --> 00:29:48.450
You give them a forced choice
paradigm, is what it's called.

00:29:48.450 --> 00:29:51.750
OK, so is it President Tree or
President Shrub or President

00:29:51.750 --> 00:29:53.260
Bench or President Bush?

00:29:53.260 --> 00:29:56.000
Bush, Bush, the kid
with the father also.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:57.600
It's still in there.

00:29:57.600 --> 00:29:58.960
It was still in there.

00:29:58.960 --> 00:30:01.800
It just takes more
work to pull it out.

00:30:01.800 --> 00:30:04.630
What you're seeing
there is not the death

00:30:04.630 --> 00:30:06.780
of individual memories.

00:30:06.780 --> 00:30:10.920
You're seeing a weakening
of a network, a network that

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:15.280
is now taking stronger priming
to pull it out of there.

00:30:15.280 --> 00:30:18.940
And just to show how subtle
network stuff can be,

00:30:18.940 --> 00:30:21.680
here's something that would
work with a lot of individuals

00:30:21.680 --> 00:30:23.290
with early stage dementias.

00:30:23.290 --> 00:30:25.890
What you do is another
type of priming.

00:30:25.890 --> 00:30:27.484
So you're eventually
going to ask

00:30:27.484 --> 00:30:29.150
them the name of the
previous president.

00:30:29.150 --> 00:30:32.300
And they first come in and
you say, oh, great to see you.

00:30:32.300 --> 00:30:32.816
Come on in.

00:30:32.816 --> 00:30:33.690
What a beautiful day.

00:30:33.690 --> 00:30:35.190
I walked here by
way of the park.

00:30:35.190 --> 00:30:37.694
The bushes were so beautiful
this morning in the park.

00:30:37.694 --> 00:30:39.610
Some of them had flowers,
some of them didn't.

00:30:39.610 --> 00:30:41.480
But bushes are so nice
to look at when you're

00:30:41.480 --> 00:30:42.860
walking through a
park because bushes

00:30:42.860 --> 00:30:44.693
are one of my favorite
forms of [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:44.693 --> 00:30:46.500
And then five
minutes later, they

00:30:46.500 --> 00:30:49.880
are more likely to
remember the name Bush

00:30:49.880 --> 00:30:53.290
out of a whole different realm
of more subtle networks you're

00:30:53.290 --> 00:30:54.590
tapping into.

00:30:54.590 --> 00:30:56.920
So all of this is the
beginning of a way

00:30:56.920 --> 00:30:59.960
of solving the problem we
had the other day of not

00:30:59.960 --> 00:31:03.740
enough neurons for them
to be grandmother neurons.

00:31:03.740 --> 00:31:05.160
More solutions.

00:31:05.160 --> 00:31:07.190
We then went to our
next realm of trouble,

00:31:07.190 --> 00:31:10.310
which was the problem of,
there's not enough genes.

00:31:10.310 --> 00:31:12.940
There's not enough genes
in that specific realm

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:15.730
of explaining bifurcations.

00:31:15.730 --> 00:31:20.150
And there can't be a gene
that specifies, OK, this

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:22.780
is where you bifurcate if you
were this particular blood

00:31:22.780 --> 00:31:25.730
vessel and a different gene
for this particular bronchial

00:31:25.730 --> 00:31:27.530
and a different
gene for this branch

00:31:27.530 --> 00:31:30.320
of a dendrite and a single--
it can't work that way.

00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:31.920
There are not enough genes.

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:34.650
What this introduces
is the idea of there

00:31:34.650 --> 00:31:40.450
being fractal genes,
genes whose instructions

00:31:40.450 --> 00:31:44.000
are ones that are scale free.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:45.660
What do I mean by this?

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:47.970
OK, here's what a
fractal gene might do.

00:31:47.970 --> 00:31:49.430
So we've got a tube.

00:31:49.430 --> 00:31:52.440
And this is a tube that's going
to be part of a blood vessel

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:55.470
or a dendrite or a
lung or whatever.

00:31:55.470 --> 00:31:56.670
We've got a tube.

00:31:56.670 --> 00:32:02.660
And the fractal rule here is,
grow this tube in distance,

00:32:02.660 --> 00:32:07.465
grow it until it is five
times longer than it is wide.

00:32:07.465 --> 00:32:10.710
The width, the opening,
and that's the simple rule.

00:32:10.710 --> 00:32:16.075
And the rule is, when it's grown
five times longer, bifurcate.

00:32:16.075 --> 00:32:17.700
So what's going to
happen at that point

00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:19.380
is just gone five times longer.

00:32:19.380 --> 00:32:21.890
And it bifurcates at that point.

00:32:21.890 --> 00:32:25.270
And what you've got is now,
because this is split in two,

00:32:25.270 --> 00:32:27.660
the cross-section is
going to be shorter.

00:32:27.660 --> 00:32:29.560
But you apply the same rule.

00:32:29.560 --> 00:32:31.960
Now with the shorter
cross-section,

00:32:31.960 --> 00:32:32.940
you have the same rule.

00:32:32.940 --> 00:32:35.840
Grow five times the length
of that cross-section

00:32:35.840 --> 00:32:37.200
until you split.

00:32:37.200 --> 00:32:39.510
And what you wind
up getting is, this

00:32:39.510 --> 00:32:43.430
is one simple fractal rule
that will generate the tree

00:32:43.430 --> 00:32:44.250
patterns.

00:32:44.250 --> 00:32:46.790
That the branchings get
shorter and shorter,

00:32:46.790 --> 00:32:48.610
the distances between
the branch points

00:32:48.610 --> 00:32:51.070
get shorter and shorter
because the cross-sections are

00:32:51.070 --> 00:32:54.300
getting-- one simple rule
and you could generate

00:32:54.300 --> 00:32:56.860
a circulatory system,
a pulmonary system,

00:32:56.860 --> 00:33:01.090
and a dendritic tree by
giving a fractal instruction,

00:33:01.090 --> 00:33:04.110
in this case, one
that is scale free.

00:33:04.110 --> 00:33:06.980
That is, independent of
what the unit is here.

00:33:06.980 --> 00:33:09.080
And this could work
within the single neuron

00:33:09.080 --> 00:33:12.710
or within an entire
circulatory system.

00:33:12.710 --> 00:33:13.810
So all of that's great.

00:33:13.810 --> 00:33:15.670
That's totally hypothetical.

00:33:15.670 --> 00:33:17.375
Ooh, fractal genes.

00:33:17.375 --> 00:33:19.250
Well, you know by now
that's got to translate

00:33:19.250 --> 00:33:21.440
into a protein in
some way or other.

00:33:21.440 --> 00:33:26.370
How might this actually
look in a real system?

00:33:26.370 --> 00:33:35.350
So suppose-- OK, so a
gene coding for a protein.

00:33:35.350 --> 00:33:37.674
This is one copy of the
protein, this is another,

00:33:37.674 --> 00:33:38.340
this is another.

00:33:38.340 --> 00:33:41.930
They bind to each other in a
way so that they form a tube.

00:33:41.930 --> 00:33:43.870
And they bind to
each other in a way

00:33:43.870 --> 00:33:47.570
that's just pure mechanical
reality of, these are not

00:33:47.570 --> 00:33:50.470
bits of information,
these are actual proteins.

00:33:50.470 --> 00:33:52.090
So it's going up
in the tube there.

00:33:52.090 --> 00:33:55.450
And suppose that the forces
are, as the tube goes up

00:33:55.450 --> 00:33:57.220
it gets more and more unstable.

00:33:57.220 --> 00:33:59.180
And when the tube
is high enough,

00:33:59.180 --> 00:34:02.610
it gets unstable
enough that these bonds

00:34:02.610 --> 00:34:06.980
between the proteins begin to
weaken, and it begins to split.

00:34:06.980 --> 00:34:09.010
The splitting
there is a function

00:34:09.010 --> 00:34:10.480
of the length of these.

00:34:10.480 --> 00:34:11.429
So it's split.

00:34:11.429 --> 00:34:13.830
And now the next one
has half the number

00:34:13.830 --> 00:34:17.679
of proteins in this one, and
thus it's that much weaker.

00:34:17.679 --> 00:34:20.360
So you only have to go
a shorter distance now

00:34:20.360 --> 00:34:22.234
before it begins to split.

00:34:22.234 --> 00:34:23.425
This doesn't exist.

00:34:23.425 --> 00:34:25.090
It is no way it's like this.

00:34:25.090 --> 00:34:27.110
But what you could
begin to see is,

00:34:27.110 --> 00:34:31.150
here's how you could turn a
scale-free set of instructions

00:34:31.150 --> 00:34:33.010
potentially into what
it would actually

00:34:33.010 --> 00:34:36.590
look like with mortar and
bricks in terms of proteins.

00:34:36.590 --> 00:34:38.402
How it might actually work.

00:34:38.402 --> 00:34:42.860
Now the notion of fractal
genetics, of fractal genes,

00:34:42.860 --> 00:34:46.620
and fractal instructions begins
to solve another problem,

00:34:46.620 --> 00:34:50.170
and this is that space problem
of how much stuff can you

00:34:50.170 --> 00:34:52.260
jam into a space.

00:34:52.260 --> 00:34:57.290
Here's the challenge here in
terms of how dense things are.

00:34:57.290 --> 00:35:00.970
In the body-- amazing factoid--
there is no cell in your body

00:35:00.970 --> 00:35:05.520
that is more than five cells
away from a blood vessel.

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:07.910
OK, you could see why you
would want to do that.

00:35:07.910 --> 00:35:10.602
But that is not an
easy thing to pull off.

00:35:10.602 --> 00:35:12.560
How do you do that with
the circulatory system?

00:35:12.560 --> 00:35:14.870
And amazing other
factoid to factor in

00:35:14.870 --> 00:35:20.610
with that is, the circulatory
system comprises less than 5%

00:35:20.610 --> 00:35:22.580
of your body mass.

00:35:22.580 --> 00:35:24.250
How can this be?

00:35:24.250 --> 00:35:29.030
You've got this system
that's everywhere.

00:35:29.030 --> 00:35:31.370
But it's taking up
almost no space.

00:35:31.370 --> 00:35:34.450
It's within five cells
of every cell out there,

00:35:34.450 --> 00:35:36.770
yet it's less than
5% of the body.

00:35:36.770 --> 00:35:38.242
And, OK, forget it.

00:35:38.242 --> 00:35:39.450
I'm not going to put that up.

00:35:39.450 --> 00:35:44.260
But what this begins to--
OK, you convinced me.

00:35:44.260 --> 00:35:45.080
So let's do this.

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:52.030
So what you begin
to do is transition

00:35:52.030 --> 00:35:56.000
to a world of fractal geometry.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:36:01.820
You've got all your Euclidean
world of nice, smiley, strange

00:36:01.820 --> 00:36:02.640
things there.

00:36:02.640 --> 00:36:07.110
You've got this
whole world of shapes

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:11.020
that are constrained by classic
Cartesian geometry and all

00:36:11.020 --> 00:36:11.540
of that.

00:36:11.540 --> 00:36:15.230
And what fractal geometry
generates are objects that

00:36:15.230 --> 00:36:17.400
simply cannot exist.

00:36:17.400 --> 00:36:19.500
Here up on top,
eventually, you will

00:36:19.500 --> 00:36:21.100
see the first example of this.

00:36:21.100 --> 00:36:22.760
And this is out
of the Chaos book.

00:36:22.760 --> 00:36:25.280
And this is this cantor set.

00:36:25.280 --> 00:36:28.060
What you do is you
start with a line.

00:36:28.060 --> 00:36:31.470
Start with a line, and you
cut out the middle third.

00:36:31.470 --> 00:36:33.330
Now for those
remaining two ones,

00:36:33.330 --> 00:36:34.810
you cut out the middle third.

00:36:34.810 --> 00:36:37.614
For those remaining four,
you cut out the middle third.

00:36:37.614 --> 00:36:39.020
And there it is.

00:36:39.020 --> 00:36:41.790
And you just keep doing this
over and over and over again.

00:36:41.790 --> 00:36:44.940
And what do you do when you
take it out to infinity?

00:36:44.940 --> 00:36:46.660
What have you generated?

00:36:46.660 --> 00:36:51.460
A set of an infinitely
large number of objects,

00:36:51.460 --> 00:36:54.520
lines, that take up an
infinitely small amount

00:36:54.520 --> 00:36:55.560
of space.

00:36:55.560 --> 00:36:58.370
It's not possible for
that to work, yet,

00:36:58.370 --> 00:37:00.140
as you go more and
more in that direction,

00:37:00.140 --> 00:37:03.060
you get this
impossible phenomenon

00:37:03.060 --> 00:37:06.560
of something approaching having
an infinite number of places

00:37:06.560 --> 00:37:09.970
that something appears while
taking up almost an infinitely

00:37:09.970 --> 00:37:11.870
small amount of space.

00:37:11.870 --> 00:37:16.640
And what this winds up being is,
it's not quite a line anymore

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:19.430
at the bottom, but it's
kind of more than a dot.

00:37:19.430 --> 00:37:22.640
It's somewhere between
one and two dimensions.

00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:24.160
It's a fractal.

00:37:24.160 --> 00:37:26.700
Its dimensional
state is somewhere

00:37:26.700 --> 00:37:28.570
one point something or other.

00:37:28.570 --> 00:37:31.440
It is somewhere between
dots and a line,

00:37:31.440 --> 00:37:33.620
and it does this
impossible thing,

00:37:33.620 --> 00:37:38.135
which is it's everywhere
without taking up any space.

00:37:38.135 --> 00:37:41.080
Or you could then push
it to the same thing

00:37:41.080 --> 00:37:42.430
in the next dimension.

00:37:42.430 --> 00:37:44.460
And this is this Koch snowflake.

00:37:44.460 --> 00:37:46.060
And it's the same sort of rule.

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:48.830
You start with the
triangle there.

00:37:48.830 --> 00:37:52.010
And the rule is, you
take the middle third

00:37:52.010 --> 00:37:54.490
and you put a little
triangle out of it.

00:37:54.490 --> 00:37:56.150
And then take the
middle third of that

00:37:56.150 --> 00:37:57.589
and put a little triangle out.

00:37:57.589 --> 00:37:58.380
And a middle third.

00:37:58.380 --> 00:38:00.588
And you just keep doing it
forever and ever and ever.

00:38:00.588 --> 00:38:03.640
And you wind up with
something that is impossible,

00:38:03.640 --> 00:38:08.970
which is an object that has an
infinite amount of perimeter,

00:38:08.970 --> 00:38:13.670
an infinite amount of surface
area, within a finite space.

00:38:13.670 --> 00:38:15.070
That's impossible.

00:38:15.070 --> 00:38:17.240
But it begins to approach this.

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:19.080
And what you see
here, this is a way

00:38:19.080 --> 00:38:21.600
of just iterating over
and over and over to jam

00:38:21.600 --> 00:38:25.860
a huge amount of surface
area into a tiny space.

00:38:25.860 --> 00:38:30.290
And thus it's somewhere but
different, sort of like a line,

00:38:30.290 --> 00:38:32.580
but it's sort of
like a plane by then.

00:38:32.580 --> 00:38:34.960
And it's got a
fractal form somewhere

00:38:34.960 --> 00:38:36.730
between two and three.

00:38:36.730 --> 00:38:40.240
It's got a fractal quality of
two point something or other.

00:38:40.240 --> 00:38:43.320
It's an impossible
object that is solving

00:38:43.320 --> 00:38:46.110
this problem of being--
in another version,

00:38:46.110 --> 00:38:50.910
having surface area everywhere
without taking up any space

00:38:50.910 --> 00:38:53.060
and being within a finite area.

00:38:53.060 --> 00:38:55.210
Next, finally,
this Menger sponge,

00:38:55.210 --> 00:38:56.990
which is the same exact concept.

00:38:56.990 --> 00:39:00.620
Again, you start with the
box up there, or the ring,

00:39:00.620 --> 00:39:03.100
and you take out
the middle third

00:39:03.100 --> 00:39:04.357
of each of those segments.

00:39:04.357 --> 00:39:05.940
And then you take
out the middle third

00:39:05.940 --> 00:39:07.130
of each of those segments.

00:39:07.130 --> 00:39:09.150
And if you are doing
this with what starts off

00:39:09.150 --> 00:39:12.160
as a three-dimensional cube,
eventually you get something

00:39:12.160 --> 00:39:17.690
that cannot exist, which is an
object that has an infinitely

00:39:17.690 --> 00:39:22.260
large amount of surface
area while having no volume.

00:39:22.260 --> 00:39:24.870
That's what it produces
at the extreme.

00:39:24.870 --> 00:39:27.980
And we got something here
that's somewhere between two

00:39:27.980 --> 00:39:30.480
different dimensions,
a fractal again.

00:39:30.480 --> 00:39:34.490
And what you see is, this is
how the body solves the packing

00:39:34.490 --> 00:39:35.310
problem.

00:39:35.310 --> 00:39:41.960
Because all you need to do is
make the circulatory system,

00:39:41.960 --> 00:39:44.530
the circulatory system
some version of this,

00:39:44.530 --> 00:39:47.120
some version of splitting
the ends of the capillaries

00:39:47.120 --> 00:39:50.740
over and over and over or making
the lungs, with their surface

00:39:50.740 --> 00:39:54.820
area for exchanging oxygen,
looking something like this.

00:39:54.820 --> 00:39:57.200
And this is how you
generate a system that

00:39:57.200 --> 00:40:00.490
is everywhere and taking
up virtually no space.

00:40:00.490 --> 00:40:02.640
Obviously, it's not
taken out to infinity.

00:40:02.640 --> 00:40:05.340
But this is how you can have
a circulatory system that's

00:40:05.340 --> 00:40:07.580
five cells away from
every cell in the body,

00:40:07.580 --> 00:40:11.000
yet takes up less
than 5% of the body.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:13.570
This is a fractal solution.

00:40:13.570 --> 00:40:15.970
All you do here
to generate these

00:40:15.970 --> 00:40:17.620
is taking some of
these qualities

00:40:17.620 --> 00:40:19.350
over and over and
over and over, and you

00:40:19.350 --> 00:40:23.840
can begin to produce absolutely
bizarre, impossible things

00:40:23.840 --> 00:40:27.530
in terms of surface area
and perimeter and volume

00:40:27.530 --> 00:40:28.540
and all of that.

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:31.060
This is how you can
use a fractal system

00:40:31.060 --> 00:40:33.362
to solve the packing problem.

00:40:33.362 --> 00:40:35.390
Now of course, as soon
as you're coming up

00:40:35.390 --> 00:40:38.370
with the notion of something
like fractal genes,

00:40:38.370 --> 00:40:42.730
you, of course, have to consider
the possibility of there

00:40:42.730 --> 00:40:44.830
being fractal mutations.

00:40:44.830 --> 00:40:47.580
What would a fractal
mutation look like?

00:40:47.580 --> 00:40:50.040
And again, most people,
most geneticists

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:51.670
and molecular
people, do not think

00:40:51.670 --> 00:40:53.040
about this in these terms.

00:40:53.040 --> 00:40:56.050
But there are people who do
who actually talk about things

00:40:56.050 --> 00:40:57.950
like fractal gene mutations.

00:40:57.950 --> 00:40:59.320
What would it look like?

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:03.840
Suppose you've got a mutation,
and it produces a protein

00:41:03.840 --> 00:41:05.870
that's slightly different.

00:41:05.870 --> 00:41:08.900
And as a result,
its got bonds here

00:41:08.900 --> 00:41:13.000
that are slightly weaker
between different proteins.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:15.540
So on a mechanical level,
what have we just defined?

00:41:15.540 --> 00:41:18.970
This is a tube that's going
to grow these proteins where

00:41:18.970 --> 00:41:22.220
it's a shorter distance
before it begins to split.

00:41:22.220 --> 00:41:25.010
Because these bonds between
them are not as strong.

00:41:25.010 --> 00:41:27.170
There is a mutation
now where, instead

00:41:27.170 --> 00:41:30.590
of growing five times
the cross-section, maybe

00:41:30.590 --> 00:41:34.010
you're growing 4.9
times the cross-section.

00:41:34.010 --> 00:41:37.660
And thanks to that mutation,
the entire branching system

00:41:37.660 --> 00:41:39.590
is going to be compacted a bit.

00:41:39.590 --> 00:41:42.570
It's not going to
reach the target cells.

00:41:42.570 --> 00:41:46.140
And these would be
catastrophic mutations where

00:41:46.140 --> 00:41:47.830
the pulmonary system
doesn't develop,

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:50.040
the circulatory system
doesn't develop.

00:41:50.040 --> 00:41:52.620
And what you would
see in those cases is,

00:41:52.620 --> 00:41:55.260
the mutation is something
that has consequences

00:41:55.260 --> 00:41:57.000
that are scale free.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:00.650
Another hint when you see some
fractal gene mutations are

00:42:00.650 --> 00:42:03.350
a small number of
diseases that they're

00:42:03.350 --> 00:42:06.950
about spatial
relationships in the body.

00:42:06.950 --> 00:42:10.090
For example, there's a disease
called Kallmann syndrome, where

00:42:10.090 --> 00:42:14.990
you get stuff that's wrong with
midline structures in the body.

00:42:14.990 --> 00:42:16.730
Something is wrong
with the septum

00:42:16.730 --> 00:42:19.650
between the nose, the nostrils.

00:42:19.650 --> 00:42:21.810
Something is wrong
in the hypothalamus.

00:42:21.810 --> 00:42:24.780
Something is wrong in
the septum of the heart.

00:42:24.780 --> 00:42:26.760
This is not three
different mutations.

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:29.910
This is some sort of
fractal mutation messing up

00:42:29.910 --> 00:42:33.840
how that embryo did
symmetry, how the embryo does

00:42:33.840 --> 00:42:35.380
midline structures.

00:42:35.380 --> 00:42:37.290
So you begin to see
ways here in which

00:42:37.290 --> 00:42:40.930
you can solve this and, within
the biological metaphor,

00:42:40.930 --> 00:42:44.580
where you could begin to get
solutions for these problems

00:42:44.580 --> 00:42:47.300
and also mutations that
can put you up the creek.

00:42:47.300 --> 00:42:48.070
OK.

00:42:48.070 --> 00:42:51.010
So that is another realm
for beginning to solve this.

00:42:51.010 --> 00:42:52.400
Another domain.

00:42:52.400 --> 00:42:55.850
And here we begin to move
into the realm of emergence,

00:42:55.850 --> 00:42:57.640
emergent complexity.

00:42:57.640 --> 00:43:01.390
Which we will first look at a
couple of crude passes at it.

00:43:01.390 --> 00:43:05.390
First, emergence driven
by biophysical properties.

00:43:05.390 --> 00:43:07.190
And do not freak
out if you don't

00:43:07.190 --> 00:43:09.860
know what I mean because I have
no idea what I mean by that.

00:43:09.860 --> 00:43:12.420
So I will explain in
a more accessible way.

00:43:12.420 --> 00:43:15.720
And this was something that
was explained endlessly

00:43:15.720 --> 00:43:17.330
by a guy who used
to be in the bio

00:43:17.330 --> 00:43:21.010
department, a developmental
botanist named Paul Green, who

00:43:21.010 --> 00:43:23.890
died about 10 years ago
way too young from cancer.

00:43:23.890 --> 00:43:25.570
He was a really good guy.

00:43:25.570 --> 00:43:28.290
He would give this
famous lecture

00:43:28.290 --> 00:43:30.830
where he would start
off and he would

00:43:30.830 --> 00:43:33.170
describe some sort of disk.

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:36.830
And the point is that the
disk, the material inside

00:43:36.830 --> 00:43:41.610
was of a softer material than
the material on the perimeter.

00:43:41.610 --> 00:43:43.440
And he'd be putting
up math at this point

00:43:43.440 --> 00:43:44.720
that I didn't understand.

00:43:44.720 --> 00:43:46.450
But it was sort of
a disk like that.

00:43:46.450 --> 00:43:51.740
And then he would show that what
happens if you heat the system.

00:43:51.740 --> 00:43:54.274
What happens if you put
heat on a disk like this?

00:43:54.274 --> 00:43:55.690
And what he would
wind up showing,

00:43:55.690 --> 00:43:58.570
going through agonizing
amounts of math,

00:43:58.570 --> 00:44:01.990
is that, when you heat a
system, the only solution

00:44:01.990 --> 00:44:04.450
for this system that's
trying to respond to the heat

00:44:04.450 --> 00:44:07.450
but in different ways on the
perimeter versus the inside

00:44:07.450 --> 00:44:11.910
is to come up with a double
saddle, a double saddle shape.

00:44:11.910 --> 00:44:13.181
And the math proved this.

00:44:13.181 --> 00:44:15.680
And I had no idea what he was
talking about when you come up

00:44:15.680 --> 00:44:18.050
with a double saddle shape.

00:44:18.050 --> 00:44:20.550
And then what he says
is, so that's how

00:44:20.550 --> 00:44:23.410
you get a potato chip.

00:44:23.410 --> 00:44:25.410
You take a slice
of potato, where

00:44:25.410 --> 00:44:27.520
there is more resistance
on the perimeter

00:44:27.520 --> 00:44:29.640
and less on the inside,
and you heat it.

00:44:29.640 --> 00:44:31.770
And the only solution
to the problem

00:44:31.770 --> 00:44:35.510
is to come up with a double
saddle potato chip shape.

00:44:35.510 --> 00:44:38.350
And if you change the
outside, the force of it,

00:44:38.350 --> 00:44:40.530
if you take one of
those great organic,

00:44:40.530 --> 00:44:42.550
"give you the runs"
type potato chips,

00:44:42.550 --> 00:44:45.540
where it's going to have the
skin left on the outside,

00:44:45.540 --> 00:44:48.520
it's going to be a somewhat
different-shaped double saddle.

00:44:48.520 --> 00:44:51.130
Because there's
only one solution

00:44:51.130 --> 00:44:52.920
mathematically to that.

00:44:52.920 --> 00:44:54.580
And then you sit
there, and you deal

00:44:54.580 --> 00:44:56.080
with a very simple,
important fact,

00:44:56.080 --> 00:45:00.460
which is, that slice of
potato knows no biophysics.

00:45:00.460 --> 00:45:02.010
That slice of potato didn't fit.

00:45:02.010 --> 00:45:05.200
There's no gene that
instructs potatoes

00:45:05.200 --> 00:45:07.040
to respond to heat in this way.

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:11.100
This was the inevitable outcome
of the biophysical properties

00:45:11.100 --> 00:45:12.930
of a slice of potato.

00:45:12.930 --> 00:45:15.810
And what he then shows
is, in plant systems

00:45:15.810 --> 00:45:17.860
after plant systems,
they develop

00:45:17.860 --> 00:45:20.000
where two shoots
come out this way

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:21.470
and a little higher
up two shoots

00:45:21.470 --> 00:45:23.540
this way and two this
way and two this way.

00:45:23.540 --> 00:45:25.360
They're all double saddles.

00:45:25.360 --> 00:45:28.300
And this winds up being
a mathematical solution

00:45:28.300 --> 00:45:29.980
to a packing problem there.

00:45:29.980 --> 00:45:32.230
When plants are
growing their stems,

00:45:32.230 --> 00:45:35.000
there is no gene specifying it.

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:37.140
You don't need
genetic instructions.

00:45:37.140 --> 00:45:41.060
It is an emergent property
of the physical constraints

00:45:41.060 --> 00:45:43.160
of the system.

00:45:43.160 --> 00:45:47.600
Another example here that's
sort of proto-emergent, somewhat

00:45:47.600 --> 00:45:49.620
simpler versions,
this phenomenon

00:45:49.620 --> 00:45:51.280
of wisdom of the crowd.

00:45:51.280 --> 00:45:53.070
And this is one that
was first identified

00:45:53.070 --> 00:45:56.700
by Francis Galton, who was
some relative of Darwin

00:45:56.700 --> 00:46:00.000
and started eugenics and
was bad news in that regard

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:01.570
but famous statistician.

00:46:01.570 --> 00:46:04.580
And being an Englishman
somewhere in the 19th century,

00:46:04.580 --> 00:46:08.310
he spent huge amounts of time
going to state fairs and county

00:46:08.310 --> 00:46:09.210
fairs or whatever.

00:46:09.210 --> 00:46:11.130
And he was at this
fair one day where

00:46:11.130 --> 00:46:14.120
they had some oxen up there.

00:46:14.120 --> 00:46:16.890
And they were having a contest
that, if you could guess

00:46:16.890 --> 00:46:19.480
the exact weight of
the oxen, you would

00:46:19.480 --> 00:46:21.289
get to milk it or something.

00:46:21.289 --> 00:46:22.830
I don't know what
the prize would be.

00:46:22.830 --> 00:46:24.550
And there were
hundreds of farmers

00:46:24.550 --> 00:46:26.409
around filling out
little pieces of paper

00:46:26.409 --> 00:46:27.450
where they were guessing.

00:46:27.450 --> 00:46:28.970
And what he
discovered at the end

00:46:28.970 --> 00:46:31.670
was that nobody got
the answer right.

00:46:31.670 --> 00:46:32.180
Good.

00:46:32.180 --> 00:46:34.260
So the owners of
this get off easy

00:46:34.260 --> 00:46:36.360
without having to give up
any of their oxen milk.

00:46:36.360 --> 00:46:38.900
But he then did
something interesting.

00:46:38.900 --> 00:46:41.980
He collected all the
little slips of paper,

00:46:41.980 --> 00:46:43.990
and he averaged all of them.

00:46:43.990 --> 00:46:47.780
And it came out to the correct
weight within an ounce.

00:46:47.780 --> 00:46:51.210
In other words, no
individual in that group

00:46:51.210 --> 00:46:54.640
had enough knowledge to be
able to truly accurately tell

00:46:54.640 --> 00:46:55.790
what this thing was.

00:46:55.790 --> 00:46:57.980
But put them
together in a crowd,

00:46:57.980 --> 00:47:00.970
and out comes the right answer.

00:47:00.970 --> 00:47:02.350
Another version of this.

00:47:02.350 --> 00:47:05.250
And this one is deeply
important in terms

00:47:05.250 --> 00:47:07.230
of Western
intellectual tradition.

00:47:07.230 --> 00:47:10.120
Back to-- is that program Who
Wants to Marry a Millionaire?,

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:11.701
does that still exist?

00:47:11.701 --> 00:47:12.200
[INAUDIBLE]

00:47:13.090 --> 00:47:14.425
In reruns?

00:47:14.425 --> 00:47:18.780
In-- OK, so it was this one.

00:47:18.780 --> 00:47:21.110
They give you questions,
and if you answer them

00:47:21.110 --> 00:47:22.964
they give you money
and it's great.

00:47:22.964 --> 00:47:25.630
And at various points, if you're
stumped you've got three things

00:47:25.630 --> 00:47:26.171
you could do.

00:47:26.171 --> 00:47:29.047
One is, they could eliminate--
you've got four choices.

00:47:29.047 --> 00:47:30.630
They can eliminate
two of them to make

00:47:30.630 --> 00:47:32.200
it a little bit easier for you.

00:47:32.200 --> 00:47:35.490
Another is, you have this
expert who you can call up.

00:47:35.490 --> 00:47:38.760
And the third option is
to ask the audience what

00:47:38.760 --> 00:47:40.144
they think is the right answer.

00:47:40.144 --> 00:47:42.310
And all the audience there
has these little buttons,

00:47:42.310 --> 00:47:45.880
so they can choose A, B, C, or
D of the multiple choice there.

00:47:45.880 --> 00:47:49.870
And what the logic is supposed
to be is, cut it down to two.

00:47:49.870 --> 00:47:51.880
Your chances are better
if you have to guess.

00:47:51.880 --> 00:47:55.061
Talk to your wise expert, who's
sitting by on the phone there.

00:47:55.061 --> 00:47:57.560
And they're going to be wise
and be able to hopefully answer

00:47:57.560 --> 00:47:58.160
this question.

00:47:58.160 --> 00:48:00.840
Or ask a whole bunch of people.

00:48:00.840 --> 00:48:02.150
And they would all vote.

00:48:02.150 --> 00:48:04.900
And any smart
contestant would choose

00:48:04.900 --> 00:48:06.770
whatever the audience chose.

00:48:06.770 --> 00:48:11.840
Because, when the audience
was asked, 91% of the time

00:48:11.840 --> 00:48:13.740
they got the right answer.

00:48:13.740 --> 00:48:17.190
They got the majority of people
voting for the right answer.

00:48:17.190 --> 00:48:20.030
And this is more
wisdom of the crowd.

00:48:20.030 --> 00:48:22.430
And this was a much
better hit rate

00:48:22.430 --> 00:48:25.420
than whoever the expert was on
the other side of the phone.

00:48:25.420 --> 00:48:28.250
One person could be
extremely expert,

00:48:28.250 --> 00:48:30.200
but they're not
going to be as expert

00:48:30.200 --> 00:48:35.250
as a whole bunch of somewhat
decent experts thrown together.

00:48:35.250 --> 00:48:38.610
This is the notion behind a
field called prediction markets

00:48:38.610 --> 00:48:43.340
where what you do is you are
trying to predict some event.

00:48:43.340 --> 00:48:45.220
For example, the
Pentagon is very

00:48:45.220 --> 00:48:47.250
interested in using
prediction markets

00:48:47.250 --> 00:48:51.440
to try to predict where the
next terrorist attack might be.

00:48:51.440 --> 00:48:54.130
And what you do is you get
a whole bunch of experts,

00:48:54.130 --> 00:48:56.130
and you ask each of them
to think about whatever

00:48:56.130 --> 00:49:00.260
the parameters are and take a
guess as to how long it will

00:49:00.260 --> 00:49:02.290
be before the next one occurs.

00:49:02.290 --> 00:49:04.320
And what you do is,
you average them up

00:49:04.320 --> 00:49:06.930
and assume there is a wisdom
of the crowd thing going on.

00:49:06.930 --> 00:49:09.660
And that will give you
lots of information.

00:49:09.660 --> 00:49:11.720
Great case of this
a few years ago.

00:49:11.720 --> 00:49:14.920
There was some
submarine or something

00:49:14.920 --> 00:49:17.850
that sunk somewhere out in
the Pacific, in the ocean.

00:49:17.850 --> 00:49:20.210
And nobody knew where
it was, but they kind of

00:49:20.210 --> 00:49:22.280
knew where the last
sighting, the last recording,

00:49:22.280 --> 00:49:23.160
was from it.

00:49:23.160 --> 00:49:25.840
But they had a whole
bunch of naval experts.

00:49:25.840 --> 00:49:28.330
And they had all of
them sort of bone

00:49:28.330 --> 00:49:33.010
up on the knowledge of what was
the water temperature and wind

00:49:33.010 --> 00:49:35.650
speeds and where they
were on the last sighting

00:49:35.650 --> 00:49:37.690
and what was on TV
that day or whatever.

00:49:37.690 --> 00:49:39.660
They got all the
information, and each one

00:49:39.660 --> 00:49:42.880
made a guess as to where
it would be on the map.

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:44.560
And you put them all together.

00:49:44.560 --> 00:49:46.620
And they had guesses
covering hundreds

00:49:46.620 --> 00:49:48.530
of square miles of ocean floor.

00:49:48.530 --> 00:49:50.680
And they put it all
together, and they came up

00:49:50.680 --> 00:49:53.850
within 300 yards of
the right location.

00:49:53.850 --> 00:49:57.990
So what we have over and over
here is this business of,

00:49:57.990 --> 00:50:02.420
put a lot of somewhat decent
experts together on a problem,

00:50:02.420 --> 00:50:05.790
and they will be more accurate
than almost any one single

00:50:05.790 --> 00:50:07.880
amazing expert at it.

00:50:07.880 --> 00:50:09.670
Under a few conditions.

00:50:09.670 --> 00:50:13.500
The collection of these partial
experts can't be biased.

00:50:13.500 --> 00:50:15.270
Or if they are,
they all have to be

00:50:15.270 --> 00:50:18.610
biased in a random
scattering of directions.

00:50:18.610 --> 00:50:20.724
And they need to really
do be somewhat expert.

00:50:20.724 --> 00:50:22.140
If you get a whole
bunch of people

00:50:22.140 --> 00:50:24.320
off the subway in
New York and ask

00:50:24.320 --> 00:50:26.416
them to guess the
weight of the oxen,

00:50:26.416 --> 00:50:28.540
they are not going to wisdom
of the crowd their way

00:50:28.540 --> 00:50:30.740
into being able to milk
the thing afterwards.

00:50:30.740 --> 00:50:34.340
You've got to have people who
have some experience with it.

00:50:34.340 --> 00:50:36.200
And you wind up seeing
wisdom of the crowd

00:50:36.200 --> 00:50:38.850
stuff going on in all
sorts of living systems.

00:50:38.850 --> 00:50:42.690
For example, here
is an ant colony.

00:50:42.690 --> 00:50:44.650
And here's a dead ant.

00:50:44.650 --> 00:50:46.560
And they're trying to
get the dead ant back

00:50:46.560 --> 00:50:47.364
to the ant colony.

00:50:47.364 --> 00:50:48.780
And when you look
at these things,

00:50:48.780 --> 00:50:51.740
they know how to get it, or
they get some dead beetle

00:50:51.740 --> 00:50:54.240
or something to eat, and
a whole bunch of ants

00:50:54.240 --> 00:50:56.350
push it over back
to their colony.

00:50:56.350 --> 00:50:56.850
Oh.

00:50:56.850 --> 00:51:00.000
Does each one of them
know exactly where

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:01.460
they should be pushing?

00:51:01.460 --> 00:51:01.990
No.

00:51:01.990 --> 00:51:04.190
What you have
instead is, each ant

00:51:04.190 --> 00:51:07.250
has somewhat of the
right idea as to where

00:51:07.250 --> 00:51:08.330
they should be going.

00:51:08.330 --> 00:51:11.660
And there are more ants that
have a reasonably accurate

00:51:11.660 --> 00:51:14.100
notion, a smaller number
that are somewhat off,

00:51:14.100 --> 00:51:16.990
and a really small number
that are way out of whack

00:51:16.990 --> 00:51:19.390
because in general ants
are kind of experts

00:51:19.390 --> 00:51:20.640
at finding ant colonies.

00:51:20.640 --> 00:51:21.847
They're pretty informed.

00:51:21.847 --> 00:51:23.680
And what you do is you
put them all together

00:51:23.680 --> 00:51:26.270
and you do this
vector geometry stuff.

00:51:26.270 --> 00:51:29.420
And it moves perfectly
in that direction.

00:51:29.420 --> 00:51:33.290
And no single ant knows
exactly where the colony is.

00:51:33.290 --> 00:51:36.870
You've got a wisdom of the
crowd thing here going on.

00:51:36.870 --> 00:51:38.562
OK.

00:51:38.562 --> 00:51:40.370
Where are we?

00:51:40.370 --> 00:51:41.120
Five-minute break.

