If you have a chance, could
you email me that website

00:51:46.560 --> 00:51:48.570
so we could post it
in the CourseWorks?

00:51:48.570 --> 00:51:49.650
That's great.

00:51:49.650 --> 00:51:52.000
OK, picking up.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:54.810
So now we are ready to
take some of those building

00:51:54.810 --> 00:51:59.180
blocks, wisdom of the crowd
stuff, biophysical potato

00:51:59.180 --> 00:52:01.720
chips, and begin to
see it more formally

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:04.480
in this field of
emergent complexity.

00:52:04.480 --> 00:52:05.990
What is that about?

00:52:05.990 --> 00:52:07.620
What we've already alluded to.

00:52:07.620 --> 00:52:14.110
It's systems where you have
a very small number of rules

00:52:14.110 --> 00:52:19.670
for how very large numbers of
simple participants interact.

00:52:19.670 --> 00:52:20.850
What's that about?

00:52:20.850 --> 00:52:22.670
Here's what emergence is about.

00:52:22.670 --> 00:52:25.270
You take an ant and you
put it on a table top

00:52:25.270 --> 00:52:26.770
and you watch what
it's doing and it

00:52:26.770 --> 00:52:28.490
makes no sense whatsoever.

00:52:28.490 --> 00:52:31.700
You take 10 ants and do it and
none of them make any sense.

00:52:31.700 --> 00:52:33.880
You put 100 and they're
all scattering around.

00:52:33.880 --> 00:52:37.580
And somewhere around, I don't
know, 1,000 ants or so, they

00:52:37.580 --> 00:52:39.900
suddenly start making sense.

00:52:39.900 --> 00:52:43.030
And you put in 10,000 or
100,000 or whatever it is,

00:52:43.030 --> 00:52:46.210
and suddenly, instead of some
little thing wandering around

00:52:46.210 --> 00:52:48.950
aimlessly, you
suddenly have a colony

00:52:48.950 --> 00:52:55.370
that can grow fungi and regulate
the temperature of the colony

00:52:55.370 --> 00:52:56.590
and all these things.

00:52:56.590 --> 00:53:00.220
And suddenly, out of
these ants emerges

00:53:00.220 --> 00:53:04.920
an incredibly complex, adapted
system, an adaptive one.

00:53:04.920 --> 00:53:08.110
And the critical point
there is, no single ant

00:53:08.110 --> 00:53:10.770
knows what the temperature
should be in the colony.

00:53:10.770 --> 00:53:12.800
Or if this is time
to go out foraging

00:53:12.800 --> 00:53:14.970
in this direction instead
of that direction.

00:53:14.970 --> 00:53:20.070
It all emerges out of the
nature of ant interactions.

00:53:20.070 --> 00:53:24.210
You've got very simple
constituent parts.

00:53:24.210 --> 00:53:27.090
An ant, much like
one box that's filled

00:53:27.090 --> 00:53:29.370
in the cellular automata.

00:53:29.370 --> 00:53:32.490
You've got very
simple rules for how

00:53:32.490 --> 00:53:34.110
they interact with each other.

00:53:34.110 --> 00:53:36.407
Ants have, I don't know,
maybe 3 and 1/2 rules.

00:53:36.407 --> 00:53:38.490
Don't tell Deborah Gordon
in the department, who's

00:53:38.490 --> 00:53:39.790
an ant obsessive.

00:53:39.790 --> 00:53:42.150
But that I may be
inadvertently dissing the ants.

00:53:42.150 --> 00:53:45.740
But they have a small number of
rules as to how they interact.

00:53:45.740 --> 00:53:48.241
If you bump into an ant and you
do this with the pheromones,

00:53:48.241 --> 00:53:49.906
you go this way, and
if you go that way.

00:53:49.906 --> 00:53:51.000
And I'm just making it up.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:52.550
They have a small
number of rules.

00:53:52.550 --> 00:53:56.900
And as long as you've got a lot
of ants doing this, out of this

00:53:56.900 --> 00:54:01.300
can emerge hugely complex
adaptive patterns.

00:54:01.300 --> 00:54:04.730
And this is what an
emergent system is about.

00:54:04.730 --> 00:54:07.020
Simple players, huge
numbers of them,

00:54:07.020 --> 00:54:10.090
simple nearest neighbor rules.

00:54:10.090 --> 00:54:13.000
And you throw them all together,
and out comes patterning.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:17.000
And there is no single ant that
knows what the blueprint is,

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:18.990
and there's no blueprint.

00:54:18.990 --> 00:54:21.610
There is no plan
anywhere that says

00:54:21.610 --> 00:54:25.260
what the mature form of the
colony should look like.

00:54:25.260 --> 00:54:27.260
There are no instructions.

00:54:27.260 --> 00:54:31.340
It is bottom-up organization
rather than top down.

00:54:31.340 --> 00:54:34.170
And you see all sorts
of versions, then,

00:54:34.170 --> 00:54:39.540
of emergent complexity
built around, again,

00:54:39.540 --> 00:54:43.290
lots of elements of things
with a small number of very

00:54:43.290 --> 00:54:48.520
simple rules about how neighbors
interact with each other.

00:54:48.520 --> 00:54:49.680
We need that board.

00:54:49.680 --> 00:54:52.220
OK.

00:54:52.220 --> 00:54:56.050
Here we have two, four,
six, eight different cities

00:54:56.050 --> 00:54:59.660
or eight different
places where ant

00:54:59.660 --> 00:55:01.650
can find good food or
eight different something

00:55:01.650 --> 00:55:03.810
or others, eight
different locales.

00:55:03.810 --> 00:55:05.900
And you were trying to
do something efficient.

00:55:05.900 --> 00:55:09.440
You need to go to each one
of them to sell your product

00:55:09.440 --> 00:55:11.760
or to see if there's
good food there or not.

00:55:11.760 --> 00:55:13.260
You need to go to
all eight of them,

00:55:13.260 --> 00:55:16.140
and you want to do it as
efficiently as possible.

00:55:16.140 --> 00:55:20.100
You want to find the way to
have the shortest possible path

00:55:20.100 --> 00:55:21.750
to go to all of these places.

00:55:21.750 --> 00:55:26.260
And this is the classic
traveling salesman problem.

00:55:26.260 --> 00:55:28.550
And nobody at this
point can solve it.

00:55:28.550 --> 00:55:30.980
There's no formal
mathematical solution.

00:55:30.980 --> 00:55:33.330
And by the time you get
to, like, eight locales,

00:55:33.330 --> 00:55:36.180
there's, like, hundreds of
billions of different ways

00:55:36.180 --> 00:55:37.300
you can do it.

00:55:37.300 --> 00:55:40.310
So how can-- you can't come
up with the perfect solution.

00:55:40.310 --> 00:55:44.000
But you could come up with maybe
kind of a good, decent one.

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:45.560
There's two ways
you could do it.

00:55:45.560 --> 00:55:49.840
First is to have an unbelievably
good computer that just,

00:55:49.840 --> 00:55:54.640
by sheer force, cranks out a
bazillion different outcomes

00:55:54.640 --> 00:55:57.700
and in each case measures
how much you're doing it.

00:55:57.700 --> 00:56:01.230
And you can get something
close to an optimal answer.

00:56:01.230 --> 00:56:04.200
The other way of doing
it is to have yourself

00:56:04.200 --> 00:56:07.280
some virtual ants in
something that is now

00:56:07.280 --> 00:56:09.810
called swarm intelligence.

00:56:09.810 --> 00:56:11.150
Here's what you do.

00:56:11.150 --> 00:56:14.100
You need to have two
generations of ants.

00:56:14.100 --> 00:56:16.395
The first generation,
you stick them all down,

00:56:16.395 --> 00:56:18.020
different numbers of
them, and they all

00:56:18.020 --> 00:56:19.520
start off in these
different cities,

00:56:19.520 --> 00:56:20.800
these different locales.

00:56:20.800 --> 00:56:25.810
And their rule is, each one
of them goes to another city.

00:56:25.810 --> 00:56:28.630
Each one of them goes
to another destination.

00:56:28.630 --> 00:56:30.670
But here's the follow-me rule.

00:56:30.670 --> 00:56:34.130
The ants are leaving a pheromone
trail, pheromone trail,

00:56:34.130 --> 00:56:35.960
and they stick
their rear end down.

00:56:35.960 --> 00:56:36.460
What is it?

00:56:36.460 --> 00:56:37.690
Head, thorax, abdomen.

00:56:37.690 --> 00:56:39.280
And they stick
their abdomen down.

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:41.130
And they've got a
gland at the bottom

00:56:41.130 --> 00:56:43.300
there, which
releases a pheromone

00:56:43.300 --> 00:56:46.710
and makes a track, a scent
track, of the pheromone there.

00:56:46.710 --> 00:56:50.410
And a very simple rule,
they have a finite amount

00:56:50.410 --> 00:56:55.290
of pheromone in there to expend
on the entire path they're

00:56:55.290 --> 00:56:57.170
making.

00:56:57.170 --> 00:57:00.290
In other words, the
shorter the path,

00:57:00.290 --> 00:57:03.040
the thicker the pheromone
trail is going to be.

00:57:05.940 --> 00:57:08.570
Now what you do is
deal with the fact

00:57:08.570 --> 00:57:11.850
that the pheromones
dissipate after a while.

00:57:11.850 --> 00:57:13.410
They evaporate.

00:57:13.410 --> 00:57:16.690
And thus, the thicker
the path, the longer

00:57:16.690 --> 00:57:19.480
it's going to be there.

00:57:19.480 --> 00:57:22.640
You now take a second
generation of virtual ants,

00:57:22.640 --> 00:57:24.230
and you throw them in there.

00:57:24.230 --> 00:57:27.760
And what their rule is,
they wander around randomly.

00:57:27.760 --> 00:57:30.690
And any time they hit
a pheromone trail,

00:57:30.690 --> 00:57:33.850
they join the trail
one way or the other,

00:57:33.850 --> 00:57:36.510
and they lay down a
pheromone trail of their own

00:57:36.510 --> 00:57:37.350
with their abdomen.

00:57:37.350 --> 00:57:40.640
They reinforce the
markings on this trail.

00:57:40.640 --> 00:57:43.770
And let 10,000
virtual ants do that

00:57:43.770 --> 00:57:47.340
for a couple of hundred
thousand rounds of generations,

00:57:47.340 --> 00:57:50.950
and they solve the traveling
salesman problem for you.

00:57:50.950 --> 00:57:54.040
Because it winds up
being, the short paths,

00:57:54.040 --> 00:57:57.850
the more efficient ways
of connecting locales,

00:57:57.850 --> 00:58:00.870
will leave larger,
thicker trails,

00:58:00.870 --> 00:58:04.110
which are more likely to
last longer and thus increase

00:58:04.110 --> 00:58:07.060
the odds that an ant
wandering around randomly

00:58:07.060 --> 00:58:09.680
will bump into it
and reinforce it.

00:58:09.680 --> 00:58:12.040
And what you see
is, initially, there

00:58:12.040 --> 00:58:13.980
will be every possible path.

00:58:13.980 --> 00:58:16.110
And as you run
this over and over,

00:58:16.110 --> 00:58:18.480
it will begin to fade
out, and out will

00:58:18.480 --> 00:58:20.670
emerge the more efficient ones.

00:58:20.670 --> 00:58:23.860
You can optimize the
outcome doing it this way,

00:58:23.860 --> 00:58:26.810
just asking virtual
ants to do it for you.

00:58:26.810 --> 00:58:30.100
And this is exactly how ants
do it out in the real world.

00:58:30.100 --> 00:58:31.870
When they're foraging
in different places,

00:58:31.870 --> 00:58:34.330
there is a first wave
of them that comes out,

00:58:34.330 --> 00:58:37.690
and they go to locales
leaving scent trails.

00:58:37.690 --> 00:58:39.840
And then there are the
wanderers that come in,

00:58:39.840 --> 00:58:42.260
and when they hit a
trail they join it.

00:58:42.260 --> 00:58:46.090
There are now telecommunications
companies that use swarm

00:58:46.090 --> 00:58:49.270
intelligence to figure out
what's the shortest length

00:58:49.270 --> 00:58:53.340
of cable they need to use to
connect up eight different

00:58:53.340 --> 00:58:56.950
states' worth of
telecommunication towers,

00:58:56.950 --> 00:58:58.150
whatever they're called.

00:58:58.150 --> 00:58:59.722
And they can sit
there and do math

00:58:59.722 --> 00:59:01.180
till the end of
the universe trying

00:59:01.180 --> 00:59:04.130
to figure out the cheapest
way to wire them up.

00:59:04.130 --> 00:59:07.540
Or they can use
swarm intelligence.

00:59:07.540 --> 00:59:09.990
And that's what a lot of
them do at this point.

00:59:09.990 --> 00:59:11.550
It works.

00:59:11.550 --> 00:59:12.920
What are the features of it?

00:59:12.920 --> 00:59:15.080
This is not wisdom of the crowd.

00:59:15.080 --> 00:59:19.140
This is not that every ant knows
a solution to the traveling

00:59:19.140 --> 00:59:22.040
salesman problem, except none of
them have the perfect solution.

00:59:22.040 --> 00:59:23.665
But put them all
together, and they all

00:59:23.665 --> 00:59:24.720
get to vote on outcomes.

00:59:24.720 --> 00:59:27.940
The ant don't know from
traveling salesman problems.

00:59:27.940 --> 00:59:30.940
The ant knows nothing about
trying to optimize this.

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:34.170
All the ant knows is one
of two different rules.

00:59:34.170 --> 00:59:36.570
If I'm walking from one
of these to one of these,

00:59:36.570 --> 00:59:39.700
the longer I walk, the
thinner the pheromone trail.

00:59:39.700 --> 00:59:43.680
Or rule number two, if I
stumble into one of these,

00:59:43.680 --> 00:59:46.380
I join it and put down
my markings there.

00:59:46.380 --> 00:59:50.400
Two simple rules,
one very simple type

00:59:50.400 --> 00:59:54.320
of sort of unit of
information in there, an ant.

00:59:54.320 --> 00:59:57.590
And all you need to do is make
sure there's enough of them,

00:59:57.590 --> 01:00:00.680
and they solve the
problem for you.

01:00:00.680 --> 01:00:02.960
This winds up explaining
another thing.

01:00:02.960 --> 01:00:06.400
How do bees pick a
new nesting site?

01:00:06.400 --> 01:00:10.117
A bee's nest, a bee's--
hornet's nest, a bee's nest.

01:00:10.117 --> 01:00:12.200
Every now and then the
bees need to leave and pick

01:00:12.200 --> 01:00:13.210
a new place to live.

01:00:13.210 --> 01:00:15.520
And how do they figure
out the good place?

01:00:15.520 --> 01:00:18.420
And there's all sorts of
criteria of nutrients.

01:00:18.420 --> 01:00:21.650
And so all sorts of bees go
out there, and what they do

01:00:21.650 --> 01:00:23.490
is they look for food sources.

01:00:23.490 --> 01:00:25.940
And they look for a place
that will have a lot of food.

01:00:25.940 --> 01:00:29.370
Maybe that's a place to
go and move the colony.

01:00:29.370 --> 01:00:32.360
So we know already, the bee will
go out and find its food there,

01:00:32.360 --> 01:00:33.240
its food source.

01:00:33.240 --> 01:00:34.450
It will come back in.

01:00:34.450 --> 01:00:37.200
And here's the colony
cut in cross-section.

01:00:37.200 --> 01:00:40.250
And what you wind up having
is this ring of bees.

01:00:40.250 --> 01:00:41.380
Here is the entry.

01:00:41.380 --> 01:00:43.509
And you have the
bee dancing going on

01:00:43.509 --> 01:00:45.800
that we've heard about in
the middle of the dance floor

01:00:45.800 --> 01:00:46.320
there.

01:00:46.320 --> 01:00:49.830
And we've already heard it's
this pattern of this figure

01:00:49.830 --> 01:00:51.440
eight while shaking
the rear end.

01:00:51.440 --> 01:00:53.365
And we know what
the information is,

01:00:53.365 --> 01:00:59.300
which is the angle tells the
direction to go out there.

01:00:59.300 --> 01:01:01.960
And the extent to
which it's wiggling

01:01:01.960 --> 01:01:05.270
its rear end is how long
you're supposed to fly for.

01:01:05.270 --> 01:01:09.230
But the final variable is,
the better the resource,

01:01:09.230 --> 01:01:13.250
the longer you do the dance.

01:01:13.250 --> 01:01:15.820
So you've got bees coming in
from all over the place that

01:01:15.820 --> 01:01:17.320
have found good
resources, that have

01:01:17.320 --> 01:01:19.090
found so-so ones, all of that.

01:01:19.090 --> 01:01:21.820
And so there's bees doing
all this dancing stuff here

01:01:21.820 --> 01:01:23.590
of different durations.

01:01:23.590 --> 01:01:26.920
And the ones who have
found the good solution

01:01:26.920 --> 01:01:30.890
to where do we want to
live are dancing longer.

01:01:30.890 --> 01:01:33.450
The ones who have found
the most efficient path

01:01:33.450 --> 01:01:36.540
are leaving a message longer.

01:01:36.540 --> 01:01:39.080
So now you bring in
your second generation.

01:01:39.080 --> 01:01:41.780
And the rule is
among bees, if they

01:01:41.780 --> 01:01:45.160
happen to bump into a bee
that is doing a dance,

01:01:45.160 --> 01:01:47.890
the bee responds and goes
where it tells you to go.

01:01:47.890 --> 01:01:51.420
So a bee may randomly sort of
bump into one of these guys

01:01:51.420 --> 01:01:52.540
and then off it goes.

01:01:52.540 --> 01:01:54.790
Actually, I'm sure it's
more complicated than this,

01:01:54.790 --> 01:01:56.860
but it's along the
lines of there's now

01:01:56.860 --> 01:01:59.010
random interactions.

01:01:59.010 --> 01:02:04.300
If one of the peripheral
bees encounters, bumps into,

01:02:04.300 --> 01:02:06.370
one of these bees
that has information,

01:02:06.370 --> 01:02:09.570
it joins in in that bee's group.

01:02:09.570 --> 01:02:12.220
And it then goes and
finds the food resource

01:02:12.220 --> 01:02:14.210
and comes back with
the information.

01:02:14.210 --> 01:02:19.560
So thus, by definition, if you
have found a great food source,

01:02:19.560 --> 01:02:21.940
you're going to
be dancing longer,

01:02:21.940 --> 01:02:25.280
which increases the odds of
other bees randomly bumping

01:02:25.280 --> 01:02:29.090
into you, which causes them to
go and find the same great food

01:02:29.090 --> 01:02:31.780
source and come back
and dance longer.

01:02:31.780 --> 01:02:34.220
And the ones with lousy ones
are coming in and dancing

01:02:34.220 --> 01:02:36.510
very briefly, and thus
there is hardly any odds

01:02:36.510 --> 01:02:37.980
of somebody bumping into them.

01:02:37.980 --> 01:02:41.090
And what you begin to
do is, you suddenly

01:02:41.090 --> 01:02:43.540
optimize where the
hive is supposed to go.

01:02:43.540 --> 01:02:45.660
Again, it's not
wisdom of the crowd.

01:02:45.660 --> 01:02:50.340
It is an emergent feature of
one generation with information

01:02:50.340 --> 01:02:53.530
based on some very simple
rules, and one information

01:02:53.530 --> 01:02:55.880
that generates
some random element

01:02:55.880 --> 01:03:00.020
and out comes an ideal solution.

01:03:00.020 --> 01:03:01.900
More versions of this.

01:03:01.900 --> 01:03:05.410
Another domain where some
very simple rules out of it

01:03:05.410 --> 01:03:08.400
emerges something very
complex and adaptive.

01:03:08.400 --> 01:03:11.160
OK, so the themes here
are two generations,

01:03:11.160 --> 01:03:13.781
the more adaptive the
signal, the stronger it is

01:03:13.781 --> 01:03:14.780
and the longer it lasts.

01:03:14.780 --> 01:03:16.700
And then the
randomization element.

01:03:16.700 --> 01:03:19.780
Another theme that comes through
in a lot of emergence, which

01:03:19.780 --> 01:03:23.730
is to have your elements
in there, your ants,

01:03:23.730 --> 01:03:25.610
your bees, your
traveling salesmen,

01:03:25.610 --> 01:03:27.290
whatever the constituents are.

01:03:27.290 --> 01:03:30.470
And now what the rules
are are simple rules

01:03:30.470 --> 01:03:33.650
of attraction and repulsion.

01:03:33.650 --> 01:03:36.120
Which is to say,
some of the elements

01:03:36.120 --> 01:03:39.020
are attracted to each other,
and some of the elements

01:03:39.020 --> 01:03:40.920
are repulsed by each other.

01:03:40.920 --> 01:03:43.460
Some are pulled together,
some are pushed apart

01:03:43.460 --> 01:03:46.520
like, for example, magnets.

01:03:46.520 --> 01:03:49.080
Magnets are polarized
in the sense

01:03:49.080 --> 01:03:51.840
that magnets only have
two ways of interacting

01:03:51.840 --> 01:03:54.940
with each other, simple
nearest neighbor rules.

01:03:54.940 --> 01:03:57.050
They're either
attracting or repelling,

01:03:57.050 --> 01:03:59.480
depending on the orientation.

01:03:59.480 --> 01:04:01.130
So here's what you do now.

01:04:01.130 --> 01:04:03.910
You take a system and
something very simple.

01:04:03.910 --> 01:04:08.470
You've got some simulated
SimCity sort of thing

01:04:08.470 --> 01:04:12.240
where you're letting the
system run to design a city.

01:04:12.240 --> 01:04:15.130
You want to do your urban
planning in your city

01:04:15.130 --> 01:04:16.800
that you're going
to construct there.

01:04:16.800 --> 01:04:19.080
And what you do is,
you can sit there

01:04:19.080 --> 01:04:24.980
and you can study millions of
laws about zoning and economics

01:04:24.980 --> 01:04:27.870
and all of that to decide
something very simple.

01:04:27.870 --> 01:04:30.800
Where are you going to put
the commercial districts?

01:04:30.800 --> 01:04:34.060
And where are the residential
districts going to be?

01:04:34.060 --> 01:04:37.920
Or you can have just a small
number of simple rules.

01:04:37.920 --> 01:04:41.230
Which is, for example,
if a market appears

01:04:41.230 --> 01:04:46.200
in some place, what it
attracts is a Starbucks.

01:04:46.200 --> 01:04:50.380
And what it also attracts
is a clothing store

01:04:50.380 --> 01:04:51.520
or some such thing.

01:04:51.520 --> 01:04:52.890
So a bunch of rules.

01:04:52.890 --> 01:04:54.500
But then you have
repulsion rules,

01:04:54.500 --> 01:04:56.770
which is, if you
have a Starbucks,

01:04:56.770 --> 01:04:59.180
it will repulse any
other Starbucks.

01:04:59.180 --> 01:05:02.030
So the nearest other Starbucks
can be this far away.

01:05:02.030 --> 01:05:03.970
If you have a
competitor's market,

01:05:03.970 --> 01:05:05.980
it can't get any
closer than this.

01:05:05.980 --> 01:05:08.980
That sort of thing, these simple
attraction/repulsion rules.

01:05:08.980 --> 01:05:10.750
And what you wind
up getting when

01:05:10.750 --> 01:05:19.050
you run these simulations are
commercial districts in a city

01:05:19.050 --> 01:05:24.000
where you get clusters of
commercial sort of places that

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:26.290
are balanced by
attraction and repulsion

01:05:26.290 --> 01:05:29.310
where you have thoroughfares
connecting them.

01:05:29.310 --> 01:05:33.320
And the more elements there
are in the two neighborhood

01:05:33.320 --> 01:05:36.920
commercial centers, the bigger
the connection is going to be,

01:05:36.920 --> 01:05:40.820
the bigger the street is, the
more lanes, the more powerful

01:05:40.820 --> 01:05:42.470
the signal coming through there.

01:05:42.470 --> 01:05:43.640
And you throw it in.

01:05:43.640 --> 01:05:46.350
And out pops an
urban plan that looks

01:05:46.350 --> 01:05:48.750
exactly like the sort
of ones that the best

01:05:48.750 --> 01:05:50.510
urban planners come up with.

01:05:50.510 --> 01:05:53.800
And all you need to do instead
is run these simulations

01:05:53.800 --> 01:05:57.490
with some very simple
attraction and repulsion rules.

01:05:57.490 --> 01:06:00.100
So you do that, and it winds
up producing stuff that looks

01:06:00.100 --> 01:06:01.520
like cities.

01:06:01.520 --> 01:06:04.360
You do that with a
bunch of neurons.

01:06:04.360 --> 01:06:07.100
You take a Petri dish, and
you throw in a whole bunch

01:06:07.100 --> 01:06:08.480
of individual neurons.

01:06:08.480 --> 01:06:10.890
And they have very simple rules.

01:06:10.890 --> 01:06:15.060
They secrete factors which
attract some types of neurons.

01:06:15.060 --> 01:06:19.040
And they secrete factors which
repel other types of neurons.

01:06:19.040 --> 01:06:22.230
And all of them are having
some very simple rules.

01:06:22.230 --> 01:06:25.080
When I encounter this,
I grow projections

01:06:25.080 --> 01:06:26.860
towards where it's coming from.

01:06:26.860 --> 01:06:29.450
If I encounter that,
I grow projections

01:06:29.450 --> 01:06:30.640
in the opposite direction.

01:06:30.640 --> 01:06:32.950
Simple attraction and repulsion.

01:06:32.950 --> 01:06:35.280
And what you do
is, at this point,

01:06:35.280 --> 01:06:38.200
you throw in a whole bunch
of neurons, each one where

01:06:38.200 --> 01:06:39.630
you throw into a Petri dish.

01:06:39.630 --> 01:06:42.530
And at the beginning they're
all scattered evenly all

01:06:42.530 --> 01:06:43.340
over the place.

01:06:43.340 --> 01:06:46.060
And you come back, and you
come back two days later,

01:06:46.060 --> 01:06:49.220
and it looks just like this.

01:06:49.220 --> 01:06:52.580
You have clusters of
neurons sending projections,

01:06:52.580 --> 01:06:55.380
and you have all these empty
residential areas in between.

01:06:55.380 --> 01:06:58.620
And if you just mark this
in a schematic way, looking

01:06:58.620 --> 01:07:00.850
from above you're not
going to be able to tell,

01:07:00.850 --> 01:07:03.330
is this the commercial
districts in a big city?

01:07:03.330 --> 01:07:05.990
Or are these neurons
growing in a dish?

01:07:05.990 --> 01:07:10.210
And you get areas of nuclei
of cell bodies and areas

01:07:10.210 --> 01:07:14.220
of projections, and it winds
up looking exactly like that.

01:07:14.220 --> 01:07:18.950
And amazingly, there was a paper
in Science earlier this year.

01:07:18.950 --> 01:07:21.170
And it was looking at
one of these versions,

01:07:21.170 --> 01:07:23.550
again, in this case
attraction and repulsion

01:07:23.550 --> 01:07:26.410
rules with ants' colonies
setting up foraging paths.

01:07:26.410 --> 01:07:29.330
And they explicitly
compared one colony

01:07:29.330 --> 01:07:32.340
to the efficiency of the
distribution of the train

01:07:32.340 --> 01:07:35.040
stations in the
Tokyo subway system.

01:07:35.040 --> 01:07:38.190
And what they showed was
very similar solutions,

01:07:38.190 --> 01:07:40.920
but the ants had gotten
a more optimal one.

01:07:40.920 --> 01:07:44.810
And the subway system had
people sitting there salaried

01:07:44.810 --> 01:07:46.750
to figure out the
best way to do it.

01:07:46.750 --> 01:07:49.355
All the ants had were
very simple rules

01:07:49.355 --> 01:07:52.710
of, if it's someone from the
other colony I stay this way,

01:07:52.710 --> 01:07:54.880
if it's someone from
mine, simple attraction

01:07:54.880 --> 01:07:55.700
and repulsion.

01:07:55.700 --> 01:07:59.330
And out comes something that
looks like this as well.

01:07:59.330 --> 01:08:03.390
So here you see that happening
with a remarkably small number

01:08:03.390 --> 01:08:04.990
of rules.

01:08:04.990 --> 01:08:08.670
Now you put it into a really
interesting context, which

01:08:08.670 --> 01:08:12.600
is something we bumped into back
when first introducing proteins

01:08:12.600 --> 01:08:16.000
and DNA sequence equals shape
equals function, all of that.

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:18.086
Molecules have charges on them.

01:08:18.086 --> 01:08:20.169
Some of them were positively
charged, some of them

01:08:20.169 --> 01:08:21.200
were negatively.

01:08:21.200 --> 01:08:22.140
Whoa.

01:08:22.140 --> 01:08:24.569
Attraction and repulsion.

01:08:24.569 --> 01:08:26.979
Positively charged
molecules are attracted

01:08:26.979 --> 01:08:28.510
to negatively charged ones.

01:08:28.510 --> 01:08:30.250
Same charged ones repulse.

01:08:30.250 --> 01:08:34.100
Here we have a system with very
simple attraction and repulsion

01:08:34.100 --> 01:08:35.550
rules.

01:08:35.550 --> 01:08:38.740
And that's the logic behind,
when one thinks about it,

01:08:38.740 --> 01:08:42.069
one of the all-time important
experiments, something

01:08:42.069 --> 01:08:45.510
that was done in the 1950s by a
pair of scientists, University

01:08:45.510 --> 01:08:47.750
of Chicago, Urey and Miller.

01:08:47.750 --> 01:08:48.990
Here's what they did.

01:08:48.990 --> 01:08:52.750
They took, like, big
vats of organic soup

01:08:52.750 --> 01:08:57.800
stuff that just had all sorts
of simple molecules in there.

01:08:57.800 --> 01:09:00.939
Little fragments of carbon,
carbon, little fragments

01:09:00.939 --> 01:09:04.370
of-- all sorts of inorganic
molecules in there,

01:09:04.370 --> 01:09:08.550
little ones in there, floating
around in this organic soup.

01:09:08.550 --> 01:09:12.149
And what they did was they would
pass electricity through it.

01:09:12.149 --> 01:09:15.600
And they did this
vast numbers of times.

01:09:15.600 --> 01:09:18.279
And eventually
what they saw was,

01:09:18.279 --> 01:09:22.490
they would come back and check,
and these random distribution

01:09:22.490 --> 01:09:25.420
of these things, of
these little fragments,

01:09:25.420 --> 01:09:29.410
had begun to form amino acids.

01:09:29.410 --> 01:09:30.740
Whoa.

01:09:30.740 --> 01:09:32.149
Metaphor.

01:09:32.149 --> 01:09:36.410
The organic soup, just the
evenly distributed sort

01:09:36.410 --> 01:09:40.370
of world of potentially
organic molecules

01:09:40.370 --> 01:09:44.020
in a world in which electricity
passes through, lightning.

01:09:44.020 --> 01:09:46.160
What had these guys
just come up with?

01:09:46.160 --> 01:09:49.603
Some in your, like,
kitchen sink experiment

01:09:49.603 --> 01:09:52.979
of the origins of life.

01:09:52.979 --> 01:09:55.560
And what people have done
subsequently is show,

01:09:55.560 --> 01:09:57.320
you don't need the catalyst.

01:09:57.320 --> 01:09:59.640
There's a whole
world of researchers

01:09:59.640 --> 01:10:01.040
who study origin of life.

01:10:01.040 --> 01:10:06.040
And the basic notion is, you
put in enough simple molecules

01:10:06.040 --> 01:10:08.980
in there that have attraction
and repulsion rules,

01:10:08.980 --> 01:10:11.870
and you get perturbations
and spatial distributions

01:10:11.870 --> 01:10:14.300
of certain ways,
and they will begin

01:10:14.300 --> 01:10:18.809
to form rational
structures after a while.

01:10:18.809 --> 01:10:20.100
Here's another version of this.

01:10:20.100 --> 01:10:22.183
And I used to do this in
class, except I can never

01:10:22.183 --> 01:10:26.030
pull this one off, and
it just became chaotic.

01:10:26.030 --> 01:10:29.250
Kid's toy, you've
got these magnets.

01:10:29.250 --> 01:10:32.440
You either have-- you
have magnets like that.

01:10:32.440 --> 01:10:34.180
And then you have
little metal balls that

01:10:34.180 --> 01:10:36.070
can go onto the magnet here.

01:10:36.070 --> 01:10:38.170
And you've got vast
numbers of them.

01:10:38.170 --> 01:10:40.490
And you can piece them together.

01:10:40.490 --> 01:10:40.990
Whoa.

01:10:40.990 --> 01:10:43.350
This is starting to look
kind of familiar here.

01:10:43.350 --> 01:10:46.720
So we have these constituents
with very simple rules, which

01:10:46.720 --> 01:10:48.860
is the magnets repel each other.

01:10:48.860 --> 01:10:49.800
They bind.

01:10:49.800 --> 01:10:50.412
These things.

01:10:50.412 --> 01:10:51.620
And here's what you would do.

01:10:51.620 --> 01:10:52.760
Here's what I would
attempt to do.

01:10:52.760 --> 01:10:54.610
First off, I would get
somebody to show me

01:10:54.610 --> 01:10:57.600
how to get the video thing
on here to project it.

01:10:57.600 --> 01:11:01.010
But you would put up a whole
bunch of these magnets in rows,

01:11:01.010 --> 01:11:04.300
not too close to each
other, nice and symmetrical.

01:11:04.300 --> 01:11:07.460
And what you do then is you take
a handful of the metal balls

01:11:07.460 --> 01:11:09.150
and fling them in there.

01:11:09.150 --> 01:11:11.530
And if you do that
400 or 500 times,

01:11:11.530 --> 01:11:13.620
eventually they
will bounce around.

01:11:13.620 --> 01:11:15.960
And amid all the
pieces flying, you're

01:11:15.960 --> 01:11:20.970
going to get a pyramidal
structure like this.

01:11:20.970 --> 01:11:24.090
One of those just like that,
it's three dimensional,

01:11:24.090 --> 01:11:24.920
you know that.

01:11:24.920 --> 01:11:27.880
You are going to get one of
those that will simply pop out

01:11:27.880 --> 01:11:32.280
of this because that's the
nature of potato chips solving

01:11:32.280 --> 01:11:34.510
their math problem
with double saddles.

01:11:34.510 --> 01:11:37.610
That's the nature of throwing
a whole bunch of elements

01:11:37.610 --> 01:11:40.060
with simple attraction
and repulsion rules.

01:11:40.060 --> 01:11:43.980
And given enough chances, throw
in enough perturbations there,

01:11:43.980 --> 01:11:47.010
and structures will
begin to emerge.

01:11:47.010 --> 01:11:50.090
And it's the same
exact principle there,

01:11:50.090 --> 01:11:52.560
these same ones over and over.

01:11:52.560 --> 01:11:54.530
So we've got some very
simple versions where

01:11:54.530 --> 01:11:56.250
you get emergent complexity.

01:11:56.250 --> 01:11:59.120
One is this version
of a first generation

01:11:59.120 --> 01:12:01.560
has directed searches
and the intensity

01:12:01.560 --> 01:12:03.430
of the signal that
it leaves afterward

01:12:03.430 --> 01:12:05.070
is a function of
how good of a search

01:12:05.070 --> 01:12:06.990
they've done, random wanderers.

01:12:06.990 --> 01:12:09.650
Then you have the
attraction/repulsion world

01:12:09.650 --> 01:12:11.940
of putting these together,
lots of elements.

01:12:11.940 --> 01:12:14.890
And you begin to get
structures out of it.

01:12:14.890 --> 01:12:17.180
Next version of
this, or next domain

01:12:17.180 --> 01:12:21.130
of where you begin to see
the fact that these rules are

01:12:21.130 --> 01:12:24.070
underlying an awful
lot of things.

01:12:24.070 --> 01:12:27.820
Suppose here you were
studying earthquakes.

01:12:27.820 --> 01:12:30.850
And apparently there's just,
like, little earthquakes going

01:12:30.850 --> 01:12:34.870
on 20 times an hour or so
all down on the Richter

01:12:34.870 --> 01:12:38.620
scale of, you know, one
quarter or who knows what.

01:12:38.620 --> 01:12:41.720
But you get enough of these,
you get a huge database,

01:12:41.720 --> 01:12:46.290
and you can begin to graph
the frequency of Richter 1.0

01:12:46.290 --> 01:12:49.090
earthquakes and how often do you
get the Richter 2.0 and Richter

01:12:49.090 --> 01:12:50.010
3.0 and all of that.

01:12:50.010 --> 01:12:52.200
And you graph it.

01:12:52.200 --> 01:12:57.500
And it's going to look
something like this,

01:12:57.500 --> 01:13:00.520
a distribution like
that, which is obviously

01:13:00.520 --> 01:13:03.240
there's a huge number of
number one categories.

01:13:03.240 --> 01:13:06.660
And it drops off until the
extremely rare at this end.

01:13:06.660 --> 01:13:09.670
There's a distribution,
which mathematically

01:13:09.670 --> 01:13:12.150
can be described, something
called a power law

01:13:12.150 --> 01:13:14.850
distribution, with a
certain angle to it.

01:13:14.850 --> 01:13:18.070
OK, so here's the
relationship between how often

01:13:18.070 --> 01:13:21.450
do you get little teensy
earthquakes and the big ones.

01:13:21.450 --> 01:13:26.630
Now instead, what you do
is something much more

01:13:26.630 --> 01:13:31.170
different from that, which
is, you look at 50,000 people,

01:13:31.170 --> 01:13:32.940
and you look at
their phone calls

01:13:32.940 --> 01:13:34.550
over the course of the year.

01:13:34.550 --> 01:13:37.390
And you keep track
of how far the phone

01:13:37.390 --> 01:13:41.250
call was, how distant the
person is that they called.

01:13:41.250 --> 01:13:44.490
And now you map the distance,
the very shortest calls,

01:13:44.490 --> 01:13:46.150
the very longest,
and the frequency.

01:13:46.150 --> 01:13:49.120
And it's the exact same curve.

01:13:49.120 --> 01:13:52.570
It's the same power
law distribution.

01:13:52.570 --> 01:13:53.670
Next version of it.

01:13:53.670 --> 01:13:56.380
This was a study that was
done, which was-- I don't quite

01:13:56.380 --> 01:13:57.580
know how these guys did it.

01:13:57.580 --> 01:13:59.920
I always get lost in
the math on these.

01:13:59.920 --> 01:14:01.860
But in this one,
what they did was

01:14:01.860 --> 01:14:04.920
they took a whole bunch
of marked dollar bills,

01:14:04.920 --> 01:14:07.570
and they started in the middle
of-- I don't know where,

01:14:07.570 --> 01:14:09.380
I think it was at
Columbia, something--

01:14:09.380 --> 01:14:11.630
and they were
somehow able to keep

01:14:11.630 --> 01:14:15.700
track of how far the bills
had traveled a week later.

01:14:15.700 --> 01:14:18.140
And asking, OK,
how many bills had

01:14:18.140 --> 01:14:20.120
traveled no more than a mile?

01:14:20.120 --> 01:14:21.890
How many five miles?

01:14:21.890 --> 01:14:24.330
And it was the exact same curve.

01:14:24.330 --> 01:14:27.010
And people now have been
showing this same power law

01:14:27.010 --> 01:14:27.889
distribution.

01:14:27.889 --> 01:14:29.930
Here are some of the things
that have been shown.

01:14:29.930 --> 01:14:32.620
The number of
links that websites

01:14:32.620 --> 01:14:34.160
have to other websites.

01:14:34.160 --> 01:14:36.480
The number that
have only one link.

01:14:36.480 --> 01:14:39.150
Power law distribution.

01:14:39.150 --> 01:14:40.230
Proteins.

01:14:40.230 --> 01:14:44.320
The number of proteins showing
certain degrees of complexity

01:14:44.320 --> 01:14:47.750
and the numbers dropping
off with the same power law.

01:14:47.750 --> 01:14:51.200
Here's one which is the
number of emails somebody

01:14:51.200 --> 01:14:52.620
sends over the
course of the year.

01:14:52.620 --> 01:14:54.369
This is the one that
was done at Columbia.

01:14:54.369 --> 01:14:56.520
They got access to
everybody's email records.

01:14:56.520 --> 01:14:58.590
I don't understand how
they could have done this.

01:14:58.590 --> 01:15:01.920
But it was a couple of million
over the course of the year.

01:15:01.920 --> 01:15:05.680
And what they showed was the
frequency, how many people

01:15:05.680 --> 01:15:08.690
were making this small of
a number of emails over--

01:15:08.690 --> 01:15:10.890
and the same power law.

01:15:10.890 --> 01:15:13.520
Then there's this
totally crazy one,

01:15:13.520 --> 01:15:17.600
which is, OK, do you guys know
the Kevin Bacon, six degrees

01:15:17.600 --> 01:15:20.000
of separation thing there?

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:20.540
OK.

01:15:20.540 --> 01:15:22.920
Someone went and did
a study about this

01:15:22.920 --> 01:15:25.340
that they got, like,
every actor that they

01:15:25.340 --> 01:15:28.930
could find who was in a
film in the last two years.

01:15:28.930 --> 01:15:31.480
And they got all of
their filmographies.

01:15:31.480 --> 01:15:34.930
And they generated their Kevin
Bacon degrees of freedom,

01:15:34.930 --> 01:15:37.854
degrees of--

01:15:37.854 --> 01:15:38.830
Separation.

01:15:38.830 --> 01:15:39.540
Sing it out.

01:15:39.540 --> 01:15:40.120
OK.

01:15:40.120 --> 01:15:42.860
And they figured it out, the
number for each individual.

01:15:42.860 --> 01:15:44.470
And then they graphed it.

01:15:44.470 --> 01:15:47.770
How many people were six
degrees of separation away,

01:15:47.770 --> 01:15:49.570
how many were five, so on.

01:15:49.570 --> 01:15:51.360
And it's the same pattern.

01:15:51.360 --> 01:15:55.150
And this one keeps popping
up, this power law business.

01:15:55.150 --> 01:15:58.960
And what you see intrinsic
in that is, it's a fractal.

01:15:58.960 --> 01:16:00.740
Because some of the
time you're talking

01:16:00.740 --> 01:16:03.441
about what's happening with
the tectonic plates on Earth,

01:16:03.441 --> 01:16:05.690
and some of the time you're
talking about phone calls,

01:16:05.690 --> 01:16:07.981
and some of the time you're
talking about how molecules

01:16:07.981 --> 01:16:09.420
interact with each other.

01:16:09.420 --> 01:16:11.680
There's something
emergent that goes

01:16:11.680 --> 01:16:14.870
on there, which is
an outcome of some

01:16:14.870 --> 01:16:18.200
of these simple
attraction/repulsion rules,

01:16:18.200 --> 01:16:21.380
an outcome of simple
pioneer generation

01:16:21.380 --> 01:16:23.030
and then random movement ones.

01:16:23.030 --> 01:16:26.386
And out come
structures like these.

01:16:26.386 --> 01:16:30.230
This winds up being applicable
in a very interesting domain

01:16:30.230 --> 01:16:33.010
biologically.

01:16:33.010 --> 01:16:36.280
OK, so now we go back to the
traveling salesman problem.

01:16:36.280 --> 01:16:39.240
And we're having now a
cellular version of it

01:16:39.240 --> 01:16:40.710
in terms of networks.

01:16:40.710 --> 01:16:44.960
You've got a whole
bunch of nodes here.

01:16:44.960 --> 01:16:48.230
And the choice that
each node has to make,

01:16:48.230 --> 01:16:50.970
in effect, is how
many connections it

01:16:50.970 --> 01:16:54.640
will make in the network
to other nodes and how far

01:16:54.640 --> 01:16:56.760
should those connections be.

01:16:56.760 --> 01:16:59.230
Should it only connect
with ones way out there?

01:16:59.230 --> 01:17:00.520
What does it want to do?

01:17:00.520 --> 01:17:01.490
That's nonsense.

01:17:01.490 --> 01:17:04.610
In terms of optimizing
a system, what

01:17:04.610 --> 01:17:08.170
do you want your distribution
of connections of nodes

01:17:08.170 --> 01:17:09.220
in a network to be?

01:17:09.220 --> 01:17:10.940
What is it you want to optimize?

01:17:10.940 --> 01:17:12.690
You want to get
a system that has

01:17:12.690 --> 01:17:17.360
very stable, solid interactions
amongst clusters of nodes

01:17:17.360 --> 01:17:19.530
but nevertheless
occasionally has

01:17:19.530 --> 01:17:22.820
the capacity to make
long-distance connections

01:17:22.820 --> 01:17:23.710
there.

01:17:23.710 --> 01:17:26.910
And what you wind up
seeing is, if you generate

01:17:26.910 --> 01:17:31.570
a power law distribution
in terms of, OK, all

01:17:31.570 --> 01:17:34.446
of my projections are going
to be within this distance

01:17:34.446 --> 01:17:37.980
and within this same
power law distribution

01:17:37.980 --> 01:17:41.600
so that the vast majority
of the nodes in the network

01:17:41.600 --> 01:17:43.590
are having very
local connections.

01:17:43.590 --> 01:17:47.630
But still there is a possibility
now and then of very long ones.

01:17:47.630 --> 01:17:51.350
You get a system that is
the most optimal for solving

01:17:51.350 --> 01:17:55.640
problems most cheaply, cheaply,
and whatever the term is there.

01:17:55.640 --> 01:17:58.510
And this solves it for you.

01:17:58.510 --> 01:18:00.810
And then you look at
brain development.

01:18:00.810 --> 01:18:03.990
So you've got neurons
forming in the cortex,

01:18:03.990 --> 01:18:07.570
in the fetal cortex,
and you've got neurons.

01:18:07.570 --> 01:18:08.980
You've got all these nodes.

01:18:08.980 --> 01:18:12.610
And they have to figure out
how to wire up with each other

01:18:12.610 --> 01:18:15.570
and how to wire up in a
way that is most efficient.

01:18:15.570 --> 01:18:17.660
What's most efficient
in order to be

01:18:17.660 --> 01:18:21.630
able to do the sorts of things
the cortex specializes in?

01:18:21.630 --> 01:18:25.770
And you now begin to look at
the distribution of projections.

01:18:25.770 --> 01:18:28.940
And it's a power
law relationship.

01:18:28.940 --> 01:18:32.000
Most neurons in the
cortex are having

01:18:32.000 --> 01:18:35.380
the vast majority of their
projections very local.

01:18:35.380 --> 01:18:37.260
But then you have
ones now and then

01:18:37.260 --> 01:18:39.360
that have moderate ones,
even rarer ones, that

01:18:39.360 --> 01:18:41.150
have extremely long ones.

01:18:41.150 --> 01:18:45.220
And you look, and this is
how the cortex is wired up.

01:18:45.220 --> 01:18:47.810
It follows a power
law distribution.

01:18:47.810 --> 01:18:49.350
And what this
allows you to do is

01:18:49.350 --> 01:18:53.140
have clusters of stable,
functional interactions.

01:18:53.140 --> 01:18:56.370
But every now and then, you
can talk to somebody way

01:18:56.370 --> 01:19:00.120
over at the other end of the
cortex to see what's happening.

01:19:00.120 --> 01:19:01.460
Interesting finding.

01:19:01.460 --> 01:19:02.620
Autism.

01:19:02.620 --> 01:19:05.610
Autism, people have been looking
for what's up biologically.

01:19:05.610 --> 01:19:06.990
And the initial
assumptions would

01:19:06.990 --> 01:19:08.406
be, there's not
going to be enough

01:19:08.406 --> 01:19:10.070
neurons in some
part of the brain

01:19:10.070 --> 01:19:11.520
or maybe too many in another.

01:19:11.520 --> 01:19:13.290
What appears to
be the case so far

01:19:13.290 --> 01:19:15.560
is there's relatively
normal number

01:19:15.560 --> 01:19:17.530
of neurons in the cortex.

01:19:17.530 --> 01:19:21.210
But then some people started
studying the projection

01:19:21.210 --> 01:19:25.200
profiles of neurons in
the cortex of individuals

01:19:25.200 --> 01:19:26.630
with autism post-mortem.

01:19:26.630 --> 01:19:27.890
Very rare to get these.

01:19:27.890 --> 01:19:30.295
And you see a power
law distribution.

01:19:30.295 --> 01:19:33.040
But it's a different one.

01:19:33.040 --> 01:19:35.100
It's a steeper one.

01:19:35.100 --> 01:19:36.480
What does that mean?

01:19:36.480 --> 01:19:39.030
In the cortex of
autistic individuals,

01:19:39.030 --> 01:19:42.800
way more of the connections
are little local ones.

01:19:42.800 --> 01:19:45.640
There's far fewer of
the long-distance ones.

01:19:45.640 --> 01:19:47.150
There are way more local ones.

01:19:47.150 --> 01:19:48.770
What does that produce?

01:19:48.770 --> 01:19:52.260
Little pockets, little
modules of function

01:19:52.260 --> 01:19:55.250
that are isolated
from other ones.

01:19:55.250 --> 01:19:58.880
And that in some ways is
what's going on functionally

01:19:58.880 --> 01:20:00.080
in someone with autism.

01:20:00.080 --> 01:20:02.820
There is a lack of
integration of a whole bunch

01:20:02.820 --> 01:20:04.650
of these different
functions there.

01:20:04.650 --> 01:20:08.880
And that's what happens when you
have maybe a mutation or maybe

01:20:08.880 --> 01:20:11.660
some epigenetic something
or other prenatally that

01:20:11.660 --> 01:20:15.610
changes the shape of the
power law distribution.

01:20:15.610 --> 01:20:16.700
Interesting.

01:20:16.700 --> 01:20:19.980
There's a gender difference
in the power law distribution

01:20:19.980 --> 01:20:22.140
of wiring in the cortex.

01:20:22.140 --> 01:20:24.540
Which is, in the
typical female brain,

01:20:24.540 --> 01:20:26.940
if this is the power
law distribution.

01:20:26.940 --> 01:20:31.260
And in the male brain
it's a little steeper.

01:20:31.260 --> 01:20:34.770
Male brains are more
modular in their wiring.

01:20:34.770 --> 01:20:37.480
What's the biggest
part of the brain?

01:20:37.480 --> 01:20:39.243
OK, we're running
out of space here.

01:20:44.990 --> 01:20:45.600
There it is.

01:20:45.600 --> 01:20:47.390
There's the brain
in cross-section.

01:20:47.390 --> 01:20:50.260
And you've got cortex
here and cortex there.

01:20:50.260 --> 01:20:52.670
And famously, here's
all the cell bodies.

01:20:52.670 --> 01:20:55.840
And when projections are
going from one hemisphere

01:20:55.840 --> 01:21:00.690
to the other, it goes across
this huge bundle of axons

01:21:00.690 --> 01:21:03.180
called the corpus callosum.

01:21:03.180 --> 01:21:07.370
The corpus callosum is
thicker in women than in men,

01:21:07.370 --> 01:21:08.200
on the average.

01:21:08.200 --> 01:21:11.310
It is thicker in
females than in males

01:21:11.310 --> 01:21:13.970
because the power
law pattern is such

01:21:13.970 --> 01:21:16.840
that there are more
long-distance connections

01:21:16.840 --> 01:21:20.664
in female networks, and thus
it's a thicker corpus callosum.

01:21:20.664 --> 01:21:22.580
The same thing is playing
out with connections

01:21:22.580 --> 01:21:23.705
like this, and connections.

01:21:23.705 --> 01:21:25.690
But this is the big honker one.

01:21:25.690 --> 01:21:29.450
You get a thinner
corpus callosum in men.

01:21:29.450 --> 01:21:34.890
You get an even thinner corpus
callosum in people with autism.

01:21:34.890 --> 01:21:38.940
Again, that hyper male notion
there of Baron Cohen's.

01:21:38.940 --> 01:21:41.850
What you have here is a
perfectly normal number

01:21:41.850 --> 01:21:46.000
of neurons, probably even
perfectly normal number

01:21:46.000 --> 01:21:48.030
of connections
between the neurons.

01:21:48.030 --> 01:21:49.790
But they're more
local, they're more

01:21:49.790 --> 01:21:53.110
isolated in the autistic cortex.

01:21:53.110 --> 01:21:55.310
There's less
integration of function.

01:21:55.310 --> 01:21:59.250
It's more isolated
islands of function there.

01:21:59.250 --> 01:21:59.960
OK.

01:21:59.960 --> 01:22:02.270
More examples of
where you can get

01:22:02.270 --> 01:22:04.120
sort of patterns coming out.

01:22:04.120 --> 01:22:09.300
Another version of it, which
is bottom-up quality control.

01:22:09.300 --> 01:22:12.950
You start a website, you
are selling some product,

01:22:12.950 --> 01:22:14.930
you are selling
books or whatever,

01:22:14.930 --> 01:22:17.730
and you're asking people
to rate the books.

01:22:17.730 --> 01:22:21.240
And you have a board of experts
that read all your books,

01:22:21.240 --> 01:22:24.030
and they're editors and they're
wise and they're learned.

01:22:24.030 --> 01:22:26.820
And they write your book
reviews and recommend

01:22:26.820 --> 01:22:28.890
which ones should be
bought and which ones not.

01:22:28.890 --> 01:22:31.290
And you get this very
successful business

01:22:31.290 --> 01:22:33.550
going so that you're selling
more and more different

01:22:33.550 --> 01:22:34.350
kinds of books.

01:22:34.350 --> 01:22:36.630
And as a result,
you need to hire

01:22:36.630 --> 01:22:38.650
more and more of these
experts to read the books

01:22:38.650 --> 01:22:40.530
and produce their ratings.

01:22:40.530 --> 01:22:43.320
And eventually that just
becomes too top heavy.

01:22:43.320 --> 01:22:44.490
And what do you do?

01:22:44.490 --> 01:22:46.700
The whole world that
we completely take for

01:22:46.700 --> 01:22:51.250
granted now, you have bottom-up,
bottom-up evaluations.

01:22:51.250 --> 01:22:53.160
Everybody rates things.

01:22:53.160 --> 01:22:57.660
And that's the world where you
punch in a book into Amazon

01:22:57.660 --> 01:23:00.210
or you look at something in
Netflix and when you return it,

01:23:00.210 --> 01:23:03.440
it will give you, people
who liked this movie tend

01:23:03.440 --> 01:23:05.240
to like these things as well.

01:23:05.240 --> 01:23:07.560
There are no critics,
professional critics,

01:23:07.560 --> 01:23:10.530
sitting there doing
top-down evaluations.

01:23:10.530 --> 01:23:13.400
This is another
realm of expressing

01:23:13.400 --> 01:23:15.660
attraction and repulsion rules.

01:23:15.660 --> 01:23:16.530
I liked this.

01:23:16.530 --> 01:23:17.880
I didn't like this.

01:23:17.880 --> 01:23:20.010
And all you need to
do, then, is throw

01:23:20.010 --> 01:23:22.880
in elements of
randomization, and you've

01:23:22.880 --> 01:23:25.650
got bottom-up quality control.

01:23:25.650 --> 01:23:28.040
And that's a completely
different way

01:23:28.040 --> 01:23:29.010
of doing these things.

01:23:29.010 --> 01:23:33.020
What's the greatest example
out there of bottom-up systems

01:23:33.020 --> 01:23:34.436
with quality control?

01:23:34.436 --> 01:23:36.160
Wikipedia.

01:23:36.160 --> 01:23:40.570
Wikipedia does not have
gray-bearded silverback elders

01:23:40.570 --> 01:23:43.350
there writing up the
Wikipedia knowledge

01:23:43.350 --> 01:23:45.580
and sending it on
down to everyone else.

01:23:45.580 --> 01:23:48.680
It is a bottom-up
self-correcting system.

01:23:48.680 --> 01:23:51.320
It is very easy to make
fun of some of the stuff

01:23:51.320 --> 01:23:53.780
that winds up in
Wikipedia, which is, like,

01:23:53.780 --> 01:23:55.460
wildly, insanely wrong.

01:23:55.460 --> 01:23:59.390
But when you get into areas
that are fairly hard nosed.

01:23:59.390 --> 01:24:01.950
Very interesting study
about five years ago

01:24:01.950 --> 01:24:05.260
that Nature commissioned, which
was getting a bunch of experts

01:24:05.260 --> 01:24:09.340
to look at Wikipedia and to look
at the Encyclopedia Britannica

01:24:09.340 --> 01:24:12.550
and look at the
hard-nosed facts in there

01:24:12.550 --> 01:24:15.160
about the physical
sciences, the life sciences.

01:24:15.160 --> 01:24:17.570
And what you got
was, Wikipedia was

01:24:17.570 --> 01:24:21.120
in hailing distance of the
Encyclopedia Britannica's

01:24:21.120 --> 01:24:22.730
level of accuracy.

01:24:22.730 --> 01:24:24.680
And that was five years ago.

01:24:24.680 --> 01:24:28.200
And it has five years of
self-organized correction

01:24:28.200 --> 01:24:29.230
since then.

01:24:29.230 --> 01:24:30.560
This is amazing.

01:24:30.560 --> 01:24:33.790
The Encyclopedia Britannica
is like written-- there's,

01:24:33.790 --> 01:24:38.730
like, 30, like, elderly, stuffed
British scholars that they,

01:24:38.730 --> 01:24:41.240
like, have locked
in a room for years

01:24:41.240 --> 01:24:42.980
who produced the encyclopedia.

01:24:42.980 --> 01:24:46.050
And these are the law
givers and the knowledge--

01:24:46.050 --> 01:24:48.120
And you just let a
whole bunch of people

01:24:48.120 --> 01:24:50.340
loose with somewhat
differing opinions

01:24:50.340 --> 01:24:55.360
about whether Madonna
was born in 1994 or 1987

01:24:55.360 --> 01:24:56.110
or whatever it is.

01:24:56.110 --> 01:24:58.110
And you throw them
all together and you

01:24:58.110 --> 01:24:59.730
do wisdom of the crowd stuff.

01:24:59.730 --> 01:25:04.320
And out comes a self-correcting,
accurate, adaptive system

01:25:04.320 --> 01:25:09.860
with no blueprint, just with
some very simple local rules.

01:25:09.860 --> 01:25:14.470
Very simple ones, which is
looking for similar patterns

01:25:14.470 --> 01:25:16.520
shared between
different individuals,

01:25:16.520 --> 01:25:17.480
and self-correcting.

01:25:17.480 --> 01:25:19.680
Where you get even
more efficient versions

01:25:19.680 --> 01:25:21.950
of that is with a
lot of websites,

01:25:21.950 --> 01:25:25.810
where not only does everybody
get to put in their opinion,

01:25:25.810 --> 01:25:28.300
but people whose
opinions are better

01:25:28.300 --> 01:25:32.590
rated have more of a voice
in evaluating somebody else.

01:25:32.590 --> 01:25:34.790
You're putting in
weighted wisdom

01:25:34.790 --> 01:25:36.800
of the crowd-type
functions in there,

01:25:36.800 --> 01:25:40.100
and out comes
incredible accuracy.

01:25:40.100 --> 01:25:40.950
These are great.

01:25:40.950 --> 01:25:44.000
There is one drawback with
those systems, though, which

01:25:44.000 --> 01:25:46.145
is, with ones like
Netflix, where it tells you

01:25:46.145 --> 01:25:48.770
you're going to like this if you
like this, that sort of thing.

01:25:48.770 --> 01:25:51.910
It's a system that is very
biased towards conformity.

01:25:51.910 --> 01:25:56.060
It's not good at spotting
outliers and sort of taste

01:25:56.060 --> 01:25:56.700
and such.

01:25:56.700 --> 01:25:59.460
What you really want to
do in those systems is,

01:25:59.460 --> 01:26:03.200
here are the movies-- of the
movies that are out right now,

01:26:03.200 --> 01:26:06.200
here are the ones that have
10% of the people think

01:26:06.200 --> 01:26:08.080
it's the greatest
movie they've ever seen

01:26:08.080 --> 01:26:10.430
and 10% think it's
the worst movie.

01:26:10.430 --> 01:26:12.540
That's an interesting
movie to see.

01:26:12.540 --> 01:26:14.630
That's when you want
to be able to get

01:26:14.630 --> 01:26:18.830
a way of bottom-up information
about the extremes.

01:26:18.830 --> 01:26:20.930
Movies that generate
controversy.

01:26:20.930 --> 01:26:23.170
Everybody's going to
love whatever it is,

01:26:23.170 --> 01:26:24.800
and that doesn't
take a whole lot.

01:26:24.800 --> 01:26:27.480
This is a way to break the
potential for conformity

01:26:27.480 --> 01:26:29.090
in these bottom-up systems.

01:26:29.090 --> 01:26:33.100
Nonetheless, overall it
winds up solving a problem

01:26:33.100 --> 01:26:37.130
without professional
critics, without a blueprint,

01:26:37.130 --> 01:26:40.130
without top-down control.

01:26:40.130 --> 01:26:42.330
So how do you wire
some of these up?

01:26:42.330 --> 01:26:44.390
Back to the cortex.

01:26:44.390 --> 01:26:47.055
And the adult cortex has
these power law distributions,

01:26:47.055 --> 01:26:49.500
and they're great
because they optimize.

01:26:49.500 --> 01:26:51.850
They've got lots of stable,
local communication,

01:26:51.850 --> 01:26:53.620
but there's still
the ability to do

01:26:53.620 --> 01:26:55.940
creative long-distance
connections.

01:26:55.940 --> 01:26:58.010
So that's great.

01:26:58.010 --> 01:26:59.110
But how do you get that?

01:26:59.110 --> 01:27:01.640
How does the nervous
system wire up this way?

01:27:01.640 --> 01:27:04.180
And it does swarm intelligence.

01:27:04.180 --> 01:27:09.450
The developing cortex does a
swarm intelligence solution.

01:27:09.450 --> 01:27:13.780
When the cortex is
first developing,

01:27:13.780 --> 01:27:18.530
what you will have is a
first generation, a pioneer

01:27:18.530 --> 01:27:22.550
generation, a pioneer
generation of cells.

01:27:22.550 --> 01:27:27.440
The cortex surface, all of
that, that there is a pioneer

01:27:27.440 --> 01:27:30.380
generation of cells
that basically grow

01:27:30.380 --> 01:27:32.920
processes up like these.

01:27:32.920 --> 01:27:36.420
And these are called
radial glial cells.

01:27:36.420 --> 01:27:39.740
What they are, they're the
ants with the first generation

01:27:39.740 --> 01:27:41.710
of setting down the trail here.

01:27:41.710 --> 01:27:43.850
They're the first
bees coming in.

01:27:43.850 --> 01:27:46.160
And what you then
have, the neurons

01:27:46.160 --> 01:27:49.190
are the second-generation
random wanderers.

01:27:49.190 --> 01:27:50.830
And what they do
is they come in.

01:27:50.830 --> 01:27:52.540
And as they begin
to develop, they

01:27:52.540 --> 01:27:55.380
have rules that, when
they hit a radial glia,

01:27:55.380 --> 01:27:57.020
they grow up along it.

01:27:57.020 --> 01:27:59.510
They migrate along it,
they throw up connections.

01:27:59.510 --> 01:28:01.870
And you do that with
enough of the cortex, which

01:28:01.870 --> 01:28:05.600
is hundreds of millions of
billions of neurons in there,

01:28:05.600 --> 01:28:09.620
and you get optimal
power law distributions.

01:28:09.620 --> 01:28:13.230
All you need are some
very simple local rules.

01:28:13.230 --> 01:28:17.440
And out of that emerges
an optimally wired cortex.

01:28:17.440 --> 01:28:22.190
And it's the same simple
emergent stuff going on.

01:28:22.190 --> 01:28:23.000
OK.

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:26.420
So how do we begin to really
apply this stuff to humans?

01:28:26.420 --> 01:28:29.090
Because it winds up being
very pertinent and making

01:28:29.090 --> 01:28:31.690
sense of some of the most
interesting complex things

01:28:31.690 --> 01:28:32.820
about us.

01:28:32.820 --> 01:28:37.300
So what's the difference between
humans and every other species?

01:28:37.300 --> 01:28:39.200
Nothing all that exciting.

01:28:39.200 --> 01:28:41.490
From a neurobiological
standpoint,

01:28:41.490 --> 01:28:45.240
you've got this real challenge,
which is, you look at a neuron

01:28:45.240 --> 01:28:47.480
from a fruit fly
under a microscope

01:28:47.480 --> 01:28:49.927
and you look at one
from us and it's

01:28:49.927 --> 01:28:51.530
going to look kind of the same.

01:28:51.530 --> 01:28:53.410
Looking at a single
neuron, you can't tell

01:28:53.410 --> 01:28:54.990
which species it came from.

01:28:54.990 --> 01:28:58.020
We have the same kind
of neurotransmitters

01:28:58.020 --> 01:29:00.690
that a worm uses in
its nervous system.

01:29:00.690 --> 01:29:03.300
We've got the same
kind of ion channels,

01:29:03.300 --> 01:29:06.540
the same sort of excitability,
the same action potentials.

01:29:06.540 --> 01:29:08.500
You know, minor
details are different.

01:29:08.500 --> 01:29:11.350
We have not become
humans by inventing

01:29:11.350 --> 01:29:15.340
new types of brain cells and new
types of chemical messengers.

01:29:15.340 --> 01:29:18.490
We have the same basic
off-the-rack neuron

01:29:18.490 --> 01:29:20.220
that a fly does.

01:29:20.220 --> 01:29:21.150
Oh.

01:29:21.150 --> 01:29:25.200
We have very similar
basic building blocks.

01:29:25.200 --> 01:29:26.830
What's the
difference, of course,

01:29:26.830 --> 01:29:30.540
is we've got 100 million
of them for every neuron

01:29:30.540 --> 01:29:32.760
that you find in a fly brain.

01:29:32.760 --> 01:29:36.430
And out of that comes
emergent properties.

01:29:36.430 --> 01:29:37.630
Great story.

01:29:37.630 --> 01:29:39.550
Garry KAS-pah-rof,
kas-PAH-rof, I never

01:29:39.550 --> 01:29:42.290
remember which
syllable to emphasize.

01:29:42.290 --> 01:29:45.980
Grandmaster Russian, chess
grandmaster in the '90s.

01:29:45.980 --> 01:29:49.120
And apparently he's rated as one
of the strongest of all times.

01:29:49.120 --> 01:29:52.350
And he was the
person who wound up

01:29:52.350 --> 01:29:55.360
participating in this
really major event, which

01:29:55.360 --> 01:29:58.710
was this tournament with
this chess-playing computer

01:29:58.710 --> 01:30:04.209
that IBM had built called Deep
Blue or Big Blue or Old Yeller.

01:30:04.209 --> 01:30:05.000
What was it called?

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:07.620
Deep Blue, Deep Blue, Deep Blue.

01:30:07.620 --> 01:30:09.250
And they played
against each other.

01:30:09.250 --> 01:30:13.470
And apparently what happened
was, in the first game,

01:30:13.470 --> 01:30:15.780
Kasparov won perhaps.

01:30:15.780 --> 01:30:19.030
And the computer was able
to modify its strategy

01:30:19.030 --> 01:30:21.630
and then proceeded to
mop the floor with him.

01:30:21.630 --> 01:30:25.120
And this was a landmark
event in computer science.

01:30:25.120 --> 01:30:27.700
This was the first
time that a computer

01:30:27.700 --> 01:30:31.090
had beaten a chess grandmaster.

01:30:31.090 --> 01:30:33.000
Amazing event.

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:34.790
Not surprisingly,
afterward Kasparov

01:30:34.790 --> 01:30:36.590
is all bummed out and depressed.

01:30:36.590 --> 01:30:39.220
And his friends were trying
to make him feel better.

01:30:39.220 --> 01:30:43.210
And they go to him and they say,
look, all you got done in by

01:30:43.210 --> 01:30:44.520
is quantity.

01:30:44.520 --> 01:30:46.370
All you got done
in by is the fact

01:30:46.370 --> 01:30:48.530
that that computer could
do a whole lot more

01:30:48.530 --> 01:30:52.040
computations than you could
in a set amount of time.

01:30:52.040 --> 01:30:54.720
I'm told, apparently
chess grandmaster types

01:30:54.720 --> 01:30:57.024
can see five, six moves ahead.

01:30:57.024 --> 01:30:59.190
And they can intuit where
the interesting ones were.

01:30:59.190 --> 01:31:03.840
And Deep Blue could calculate
every single possible outcome,

01:31:03.840 --> 01:31:05.747
like, seven, eight
moves in advance.

01:31:05.747 --> 01:31:07.580
And every time, it would
simply pick the one

01:31:07.580 --> 01:31:08.850
that was the best outcome.

01:31:08.850 --> 01:31:12.160
It was like generating solutions
to the traveling salesman

01:31:12.160 --> 01:31:12.920
problem.

01:31:12.920 --> 01:31:16.090
Kasparov didn't have a
chance because the computer

01:31:16.090 --> 01:31:18.850
could simply generate
enough solutions

01:31:18.850 --> 01:31:20.400
to pick the right one.

01:31:20.400 --> 01:31:21.950
So all of them
are saying to him,

01:31:21.950 --> 01:31:24.850
you should not be depressed
because all that computer had

01:31:24.850 --> 01:31:27.180
going for it was quantity.

01:31:27.180 --> 01:31:29.030
And what he said
in response was,

01:31:29.030 --> 01:31:33.520
yeah, but with enough
quantity you invent quality.

01:31:33.520 --> 01:31:35.890
And that's the exact
equivalent of one ant

01:31:35.890 --> 01:31:38.570
makes no sense and 10,000 do.

01:31:38.570 --> 01:31:41.180
That's the exact equivalent,
with enough of these elements

01:31:41.180 --> 01:31:42.510
here, you optimize.

01:31:42.510 --> 01:31:44.610
We do not have
fancy neurons that

01:31:44.610 --> 01:31:46.690
are different than
in any other species.

01:31:46.690 --> 01:31:48.500
We've just got more of them.

01:31:48.500 --> 01:31:52.800
And simple nearest neighbor
rules, and you throw a million

01:31:52.800 --> 01:31:54.760
of them together and
you get a fruit fly.

01:31:54.760 --> 01:31:56.640
And you throw 100
billion of them together

01:31:56.640 --> 01:32:00.030
and you get poetry and you get
symphonies and you get theology

01:32:00.030 --> 01:32:01.180
and you get all of that.

01:32:01.180 --> 01:32:03.520
And it's the same
building blocks.

01:32:03.520 --> 01:32:07.070
With enough quantity,
you invent quality.

01:32:07.070 --> 01:32:09.310
And this is the punch
line that came out

01:32:09.310 --> 01:32:11.710
of really important
work a few years ago.

01:32:11.710 --> 01:32:14.830
OK, we're now, what, 10
years, I think, into having

01:32:14.830 --> 01:32:16.620
the human genome sequenced.

01:32:16.620 --> 01:32:20.850
And about five years ago they
sequenced the chimp genome.

01:32:20.850 --> 01:32:21.660
Soundbite.

01:32:21.660 --> 01:32:23.280
Everybody learned
from whenever back

01:32:23.280 --> 01:32:27.340
when is that the human and
chimp share 98% of its DNA.

01:32:27.340 --> 01:32:32.030
So finally you had these two
gigantic rolls of print-out.

01:32:32.030 --> 01:32:33.940
And here is the
entire human genome

01:32:33.940 --> 01:32:35.530
and here's the entire chimp one.

01:32:35.530 --> 01:32:37.430
And somebody could
finally sit there

01:32:37.430 --> 01:32:40.520
and compare them and compare
them and see, indeed,

01:32:40.520 --> 01:32:42.260
is it 98% shared?

01:32:42.260 --> 01:32:43.730
And that winds up
being the answer,

01:32:43.730 --> 01:32:46.620
even though what that number
actually means is debatable.

01:32:46.620 --> 01:32:51.250
But that brings up the question,
of course, what's the 2%?

01:32:51.250 --> 01:32:53.900
What's the 2% that differs?

01:32:53.900 --> 01:32:57.351
And what has come out of that
have been some very interesting

01:32:57.351 --> 01:32:57.850
findings.

01:32:57.850 --> 01:32:59.980
Some that were
mentioned earlier on,

01:32:59.980 --> 01:33:01.890
which is, they are
disproportionately

01:33:01.890 --> 01:33:06.610
coding for transcription
factors and splicing enzymes

01:33:06.610 --> 01:33:10.290
and, OK, that amplification
of network stuff.

01:33:10.290 --> 01:33:15.980
It is preferentially coding for
non-coding regions, differing

01:33:15.980 --> 01:33:18.130
but non-- all the
stuff from back,

01:33:18.130 --> 01:33:21.160
that lecture for getting
macroevolutionary changes.

01:33:21.160 --> 01:33:23.520
That's how you get a
different species coming out.

01:33:23.520 --> 01:33:25.650
But how about other
types of genes?

01:33:25.650 --> 01:33:27.580
What were some of
the key differences?

01:33:27.580 --> 01:33:30.090
Here was one big difference.

01:33:30.090 --> 01:33:34.230
We have about 1,000 fewer genes
for our olfactory receptors

01:33:34.230 --> 01:33:35.730
than chimps do.

01:33:35.730 --> 01:33:37.900
They've been inactivated in us.

01:33:37.900 --> 01:33:39.820
They're called
pseudogenes in us.

01:33:39.820 --> 01:33:41.000
They don't express.

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:44.250
And that's about half of
the difference in the genome

01:33:44.250 --> 01:33:45.880
between humans and chimps.

01:33:45.880 --> 01:33:47.880
If you want to turn
a chimp into a human,

01:33:47.880 --> 01:33:51.200
you're halfway there if you just
give it a lousy sense of smell.

01:33:51.200 --> 01:33:53.720
That's half the
genetic differences?

01:33:53.720 --> 01:33:55.270
What other
differences are there?

01:33:55.270 --> 01:33:58.860
There were ones having to
do with morphology, bone

01:33:58.860 --> 01:34:01.850
development, probably
bipedalism versus being

01:34:01.850 --> 01:34:03.160
a partial quadruped.

01:34:03.160 --> 01:34:05.840
There are ones having to do
with hair development, which

01:34:05.840 --> 01:34:08.380
is why chimps have all the
hair on them and only those,

01:34:08.380 --> 01:34:11.260
like, disturbing people with
the hair on their shoulders

01:34:11.260 --> 01:34:12.370
have that much hair.

01:34:12.370 --> 01:34:15.480
So that's-- there's differences
in some reproductive-related

01:34:15.480 --> 01:34:16.014
genes.

01:34:16.014 --> 01:34:17.930
You don't want to mate
with them, all of that.

01:34:17.930 --> 01:34:20.520
And then you say,
where's the genes

01:34:20.520 --> 01:34:22.040
having to do with the brain?

01:34:22.040 --> 01:34:23.780
Are there any differences there?

01:34:23.780 --> 01:34:27.090
And there turned out
to be very, very few.

01:34:27.090 --> 01:34:31.080
And they turned out to
be very, very logical.

01:34:31.080 --> 01:34:34.270
The handful that differ
seem to have something

01:34:34.270 --> 01:34:38.180
to do with cell division.

01:34:38.180 --> 01:34:42.840
Have something to do with how
many rounds of cell division

01:34:42.840 --> 01:34:44.880
these cells go through.

01:34:44.880 --> 01:34:47.570
And what you have is,
the human versions

01:34:47.570 --> 01:34:50.160
go through more rounds.

01:34:50.160 --> 01:34:52.240
And calculations have
been done looking

01:34:52.240 --> 01:34:54.730
at the average number of
neurons that each progenitor

01:34:54.730 --> 01:34:57.280
cell generates, say, during
cortical development.

01:34:57.280 --> 01:34:59.230
And if you start with
the number of neurons

01:34:59.230 --> 01:35:01.690
that you find in a
rhesus monkey brain

01:35:01.690 --> 01:35:05.530
and have it do three or four
more rounds of cell division,

01:35:05.530 --> 01:35:08.910
you get a human brain
in terms of the numbers.

01:35:08.910 --> 01:35:12.800
Qualitatively, it's
the exact same neurons.

01:35:12.800 --> 01:35:14.480
All that differs is quantity.

01:35:14.480 --> 01:35:16.390
And you put enough
of these together

01:35:16.390 --> 01:35:18.410
and you go from
tools, which are meant

01:35:18.410 --> 01:35:21.950
to get little termites
out, into human technology,

01:35:21.950 --> 01:35:25.230
the difference between us
and them is one of quantity.

01:35:25.230 --> 01:35:28.760
Throw enough neurons in
there, and out begins

01:35:28.760 --> 01:35:32.930
emerging all these
distinctive human things.

01:35:32.930 --> 01:35:35.070
So what does that do?

01:35:35.070 --> 01:35:37.010
That begins to, for
one thing, underline

01:35:37.010 --> 01:35:39.490
what the main genetics
are about in terms

01:35:39.490 --> 01:35:41.660
of the genetic differences
in the brain between us

01:35:41.660 --> 01:35:44.500
and, say, chimps are
genes that free you

01:35:44.500 --> 01:35:46.440
from genetic influences.

01:35:46.440 --> 01:35:50.537
Because those are not
specifying what sort of cells

01:35:50.537 --> 01:35:52.370
you generate in larger
numbers in the brain.

01:35:52.370 --> 01:35:54.290
They're not specifying
connections.

01:35:54.290 --> 01:35:56.720
They're just specifying
larger quantity.

01:35:56.720 --> 01:36:01.130
And all this stuff goes to work
and out comes a human brain

01:36:01.130 --> 01:36:03.280
instead of a chimp one.

01:36:03.280 --> 01:36:05.230
OK, so what does this
whole subject get us?

01:36:05.230 --> 01:36:08.620
The chaos stuff, the
complexity emergent stuff.

01:36:08.620 --> 01:36:11.700
What are some of the themes that
come through with all of it?

01:36:11.700 --> 01:36:15.080
The first one is this
emphasis on quantity.

01:36:15.080 --> 01:36:17.760
You want to get a very,
very fancy system.

01:36:17.760 --> 01:36:21.770
You don't necessarily have
to invent a new type of ant

01:36:21.770 --> 01:36:25.230
or a new type of 0 or
1 in a binary system

01:36:25.230 --> 01:36:27.250
or a new type of neuron.

01:36:27.250 --> 01:36:29.150
You could do it with quantity.

01:36:29.150 --> 01:36:32.700
You get quality, you get
excellence, you get complexity,

01:36:32.700 --> 01:36:37.190
you get adaptive optimization
with huge numbers of elements

01:36:37.190 --> 01:36:39.290
with the very simple rules.

01:36:39.290 --> 01:36:41.160
What's the next theme
that comes out of it?

01:36:41.160 --> 01:36:43.990
One that is totally
counterintuitive.

01:36:43.990 --> 01:36:45.760
Once again, like
this whole subject

01:36:45.760 --> 01:36:48.140
that shoots reductionism
down the drain,

01:36:48.140 --> 01:36:49.830
totally counterintuitive.

01:36:49.830 --> 01:36:55.120
The simpler the constituent
parts, the better.

01:36:55.120 --> 01:36:58.450
Fancy, complicated ants that
are specialized and have

01:36:58.450 --> 01:37:00.040
all sorts of different rules.

01:37:00.040 --> 01:37:02.810
They are not going to
generate swarm intelligence

01:37:02.810 --> 01:37:07.340
as effectively as do systems
with the simpler elements.

01:37:07.340 --> 01:37:10.780
The more simple the building
blocks are, the better.

01:37:10.780 --> 01:37:12.940
Something else that
is intrinsic to all

01:37:12.940 --> 01:37:14.880
of this, which runs
counter to all sorts

01:37:14.880 --> 01:37:19.310
of rational intuitions, which
is more random interactions

01:37:19.310 --> 01:37:21.680
make for better, more
adaptive networks.

01:37:21.680 --> 01:37:24.710
You want lots of
random noise thrown

01:37:24.710 --> 01:37:28.660
in there because that's how you
stumble onto optimal solutions.

01:37:28.660 --> 01:37:31.130
Randomness is a good thing.

01:37:31.130 --> 01:37:34.560
And remember, right at the time
that we're making new neurons

01:37:34.560 --> 01:37:38.350
in the cortex, that's when you
induce the transposable events

01:37:38.350 --> 01:37:39.370
in the genome.

01:37:39.370 --> 01:37:43.900
That's where you juggle the
DNA producing randomness there.

01:37:43.900 --> 01:37:45.790
Randomness is a good thing.

01:37:45.790 --> 01:37:49.520
Randomness adds to the
excellence of networks

01:37:49.520 --> 01:37:50.490
What else?

01:37:50.490 --> 01:37:52.620
Next thing as a theme
that comes out of it

01:37:52.620 --> 01:37:57.100
is the power of
gradients of information.

01:37:57.100 --> 01:38:00.960
Things that guide you,
you a cell, you an ant,

01:38:00.960 --> 01:38:03.510
you a commercial district.

01:38:03.510 --> 01:38:05.890
Things that can guide
you towards things,

01:38:05.890 --> 01:38:08.530
things that can
repel you, gradients

01:38:08.530 --> 01:38:10.932
of attraction and repulsion.

01:38:10.932 --> 01:38:12.390
And that's exactly
what's going on.

01:38:12.390 --> 01:38:14.750
There is a gradient
in magnets when

01:38:14.750 --> 01:38:18.060
they're this close and the power
that they have is dropping off.

01:38:18.060 --> 01:38:20.670
As they move,
gradients provide a lot

01:38:20.670 --> 01:38:23.530
of the optimization
in these systems.

01:38:23.530 --> 01:38:28.030
Very, very important as well is
nearest neighbor interactions.

01:38:28.030 --> 01:38:30.420
These are not just a
handful of simple rules

01:38:30.420 --> 01:38:33.250
about how you're interacting
with somebody in Chicago.

01:38:33.250 --> 01:38:36.610
These are all how you
interact with another ant,

01:38:36.610 --> 01:38:40.400
another bee when you bump
into it, a glial cell.

01:38:40.400 --> 01:38:43.830
Local interactions
with simple rules.

01:38:43.830 --> 01:38:44.820
Something else.

01:38:44.820 --> 01:38:47.030
Another one that
runs totally counter

01:38:47.030 --> 01:38:49.930
to intuition, which
is generalists

01:38:49.930 --> 01:38:53.740
work better in these
systems than specialists do.

01:38:53.740 --> 01:38:56.470
Generalists are more
likely to come up

01:38:56.470 --> 01:38:59.380
with these adaptive outcomes.

01:38:59.380 --> 01:39:02.730
OK, so what does all of
this mean on a larger level?

01:39:02.730 --> 01:39:06.350
And what I think is
that this is where

01:39:06.350 --> 01:39:09.460
the complexity of human brains
and human behaviors come from,

01:39:09.460 --> 01:39:11.340
these emergent properties.

01:39:11.340 --> 01:39:14.130
And this is now a generation
or two into people

01:39:14.130 --> 01:39:15.750
thinking about this stuff.

01:39:15.750 --> 01:39:19.040
And it is incredibly
hard to think about.

01:39:19.040 --> 01:39:21.700
And most of the work
I do and my peers do

01:39:21.700 --> 01:39:24.170
is reductive stuff
that is very limited.

01:39:24.170 --> 01:39:26.770
And like, I don't
understand how to think

01:39:26.770 --> 01:39:28.040
about it in this other way.

01:39:28.040 --> 01:39:30.020
And the odds are,
you guys are not

01:39:30.020 --> 01:39:31.990
going to be good
enough at it either.

01:39:31.990 --> 01:39:35.610
You're good enough that you were
a first generation growing up

01:39:35.610 --> 01:39:37.540
that knows, if you
want to find out

01:39:37.540 --> 01:39:39.200
if you're going to
like a movie or not,

01:39:39.200 --> 01:39:42.330
you don't need to have
somebody with expertise

01:39:42.330 --> 01:39:45.720
and a label on their forehead
and a blueprint and top down.

01:39:45.720 --> 01:39:47.330
You don't need critics anymore.

01:39:47.330 --> 01:39:49.170
You have bottom-up systems.

01:39:49.170 --> 01:39:51.620
You guys who are first
generation growing up

01:39:51.620 --> 01:39:53.520
thinking in that way.

01:39:53.520 --> 01:39:55.400
What's a consequence of that?

01:39:55.400 --> 01:39:57.660
You are beginning to get
better at this stuff.

01:39:57.660 --> 01:40:00.872
And my guess is, it's not
until, like, your grandkids

01:40:00.872 --> 01:40:02.580
that you're going to
have people thinking

01:40:02.580 --> 01:40:05.340
so much in the emergent
systems that we're finally

01:40:05.340 --> 01:40:07.910
going to be able to figure
out what the brain is doing.

01:40:07.910 --> 01:40:10.570
And where you see
there is all sorts

01:40:10.570 --> 01:40:12.280
of things that can happen.

01:40:12.280 --> 01:40:14.860
If there was more
bottom-up communication

01:40:14.860 --> 01:40:16.890
in the trenches in
World War I, they

01:40:16.890 --> 01:40:18.530
would have stopped the war.

01:40:18.530 --> 01:40:20.970
All these emergent
things bottom up.

01:40:20.970 --> 01:40:24.480
We've now had
revolutions when Marcos

01:40:24.480 --> 01:40:25.970
was overthrown in
the Philippines

01:40:25.970 --> 01:40:28.310
back when that was
basically bloodless.

01:40:28.310 --> 01:40:29.970
When the Czech
revolution occurred,

01:40:29.970 --> 01:40:31.580
it was called the
Velvet Revolution

01:40:31.580 --> 01:40:33.410
because there was no violence.

01:40:33.410 --> 01:40:36.220
All they had to do was get
enough people in the town

01:40:36.220 --> 01:40:39.430
square in the capital
and paralyze the country,

01:40:39.430 --> 01:40:40.950
and they took it over.

01:40:40.950 --> 01:40:43.730
I will predict that
within our lifetime

01:40:43.730 --> 01:40:45.330
there is going to
be a revolution

01:40:45.330 --> 01:40:47.800
in some country at
some point where nobody

01:40:47.800 --> 01:40:49.540
leaves their living rooms.

01:40:49.540 --> 01:40:52.380
All they do is do
something online

01:40:52.380 --> 01:40:54.690
with some emergent
bottom-up thing

01:40:54.690 --> 01:40:58.610
and they collapse the government
and do it in and no one

01:40:58.610 --> 01:41:01.270
will have to leave their
living room because it will be

01:41:01.270 --> 01:41:03.670
all emergent things coming up.

01:41:03.670 --> 01:41:05.650
The final couple of points here.

01:41:05.650 --> 01:41:10.060
First one is, all that chaotic,
strange, attractor stuff, all

01:41:10.060 --> 01:41:12.360
of us spend a lot
of time thinking

01:41:12.360 --> 01:41:16.570
about how we're not quite
up to the ideal this or not.

01:41:16.570 --> 01:41:18.750
We're not at the
ideal appearance.

01:41:18.750 --> 01:41:20.250
We're not at the
ideal intelligence.

01:41:20.250 --> 01:41:22.140
We're not at the ideal
choice of perfume.

01:41:22.140 --> 01:41:23.590
We're not at the ideal anything.

01:41:23.590 --> 01:41:25.815
What strange attractors
and chaos shows

01:41:25.815 --> 01:41:28.800
you is the notion that
there is an ideal,

01:41:28.800 --> 01:41:32.750
that there is an essentialist
optimal, whatever, is a myth.

01:41:32.750 --> 01:41:35.590
We are all deviating
from the optima

01:41:35.590 --> 01:41:39.670
because the optima is just
an emergent, imaginary thing.

01:41:39.670 --> 01:41:42.600
The other final point is,
something that you guys are

01:41:42.600 --> 01:41:45.670
going to be much better at
than any previous generation,

01:41:45.670 --> 01:41:47.450
which, if you grow
up thinking, when

01:41:47.450 --> 01:41:49.590
I want to find out if
a movie is good or not,

01:41:49.590 --> 01:41:53.550
I do bottom-up stuff, you
are growing up with a mindset

01:41:53.550 --> 01:41:55.970
that you don't need blueprints.

01:41:55.970 --> 01:41:59.150
You don't need
top-down blueprints.

01:41:59.150 --> 01:42:01.680
And implicit in
that, when you look

01:42:01.680 --> 01:42:05.820
at how you can get complex,
adaptive, optimized systems

01:42:05.820 --> 01:42:08.140
without blueprints is
the fact that, if you

01:42:08.140 --> 01:42:10.820
don't need blueprints,
you don't need somebody

01:42:10.820 --> 01:42:12.610
who makes the blueprints.

01:42:12.610 --> 01:42:15.090
And it will be a lot
easier to comprehend that

01:42:15.090 --> 01:42:16.410
as being the case.

01:42:16.410 --> 01:42:20.900
You don't have to have a
source of top-down instruction

01:42:20.900 --> 01:42:22.747
if you don't need a blueprint.

